,Recommended,256290,17180272,"Posted: 22 July, 2015",all,Zeemond,"More than likely one of the best game ubisoft has given us in a while. It is simple, poetic and enthralling. The PRG mechanics are effective and can be understood by newcommers or veteran alike. It remind me a bit of Grandia 1, if it was a poetic experience rather than an epic quest across the world. The character are likeable and the gameplay is surprisingly varied between the puzzles, exploration and story.Definitely worth the time!P.S. be warned, it will install Uplay for you to play it, if this matters to you.-Lost"
,Recommended,256290,10076812,"Posted: 10 May, 2014",all,Canti,"Ubisoft has done something truly special with Child of Light, a product that resulted not from trying to appeal to the widest audience or focus testers, but a product that genuinely conveys the heart of those involved in making it happen.You play the role of Aurora, an Austrian princess who is trapped in the strange land of Lemuria trying to return home to her father. Along her journey, you will find various landscapes to explore, with secrets and collectibles hidden in every nook and cranny, a few optional side missions and a cast of endearing characters to aid you.Gameplay is centred on the open exploration of the world, and a turn-based combat system.While not in battle, you will be flying around the various lands of Lemuria, manoeuvring through various terrain obstacles and simple environmental puzzles, searching for a way home (and treasure!) with your firefly helper Igniculus who serves to activate certain locks you can’t reach, light up dark caves and also to stun enemies with the blinding light he emits. Additionally, you will find various characters who will provide side quests or even join your party.There are roughly 8 different party members, who range from a cowardly wizard, to a pair of jester siblings and provide entertaining dialog that is curiously written entirely in rhyme. While this is entertaining and sometimes impressive, it does make it more difficult to become emotionally attached to any of the characters, as a Shakespearean script is far from natural-sounding. Regardless, their personalities are still differentiated enough for each one to shine and leave a lasting impression and this should be considered a feat of writing on its own merit.The combat system is an interesting take on the traditional turn-based JRPG-style combat. In a similar way to the ATB system in Final Fantasy games, your attacks are based on a timer. Once the timer nears the end, you prepare an attack, but if the enemy manages to spring their attack before you have launched yours, it causes your attack to be “interrupted” and sends your timer further back. Likewise, you can do the same thing to your opponents. Igniculus helps out here too, by slowing your opponents so their attack bar will fill slower, but also by healing you or your allies and grabbing health/mana when he can. It’s simple to learn, but feels very rewarding once you’ve managed to nail the fine art of timing your attacks. Other familiar RPG mechanics include elemental attributes, random loot and a variety of potions that restore health, mana and provide buffs.You will participate in each battle alongside a party member. You can swap between other party members when your turn to attack comes without wasting a turn, meaning it’s very easy to adjust your strategy by utilising the various skills of your different partners. Each has a unique skill tree that expands as you spend ability points for levelling up through experience in battle. Some characters focus on damage, some focus on buffs or working in elemental benefits.Each part of Lemuria is a hand-painted masterpiece. The Ubi-Art game engine works the same visual magic as it did for the previous Rayman games, with a combination of high-resolution, 2D artwork spread over a multitude of parallax layers that results in every screen appearing unique from all the rest, with very few assets re-used. The watercolour artwork itself is both warm in its choice of colours and at the same time often melancholy, with ruined buildings and overgrown monuments in both the background and foreground hinting at a more peaceful past. The audio also adds to the atmosphere, with exploration music consisting of a few slow-paced piano scores, jumping to more frantic, orchestrated pieces during battles.Child of Light is let down only by its short length and by the plethora of “cash grab” DLC’s that were released at launch. But do not be discouraged, the game is presented in a way that uses every artistic medium available to it to craft an elegant presentation from an already highly competent game. It may be a short adventure, clocking in at around 10-14 hours for the core game, but the pacing of the story and diamond-like polish of the gameplay mechanics ensure that every hour is enjoyable while at the same time never overstaying its welcome.Pros:~Beautiful eye-candy artwork from start to finish~Fantastic writing feels like you’re part of a storybook~Wonderful soundtrack~Perfectly balanced gameplay mechanics, challenging without being unfairCons:~Day-one DLC, including a locked party member~Animation on some characters appears cheap~Main game will be too short for some to justify the price"
,Not Recommended,256290,10467211,"Posted: 13 June, 2014",all,mosaicorange,"Played it on hard and beat it, Played New Game + on hard and beat it again. Took me roughly 36 hours. Got all the confessions, collected all the coffers and stardust twice and completed all the side missions twice. The only items I used were Stardust and Revive potions.The Good:- The artwork, if you’re into that look.- Combat, though at times it could be incredibly frustrating and it was basically just all about timing your attacks.The Okay:- The DLC is all purely cosmetic or stat boosting (The Golem is an awful character by the way).- Not too many launch day bugs (as compared to other titles released by UbiSoft)- The story is simple, but decent.The Bad:- In New Game + mode you couldn't speed past cutscenes. It drove me absolutely crazy that I had to listen to the dialogue over again.- The writing is just terrible. They force every sentence to a rhyming structure, and they don't even do that well.- The puzzles are simplistic in nature and few and far between, don’t expect anything that requires actual thought.- The crafting system, why does it even exist? It lacks any sort of depth, and the game is easily played on hard mode while ignoring it.The Ugly:- Uplay on launch day of course was acting up- Uplay on Watch_Dogs Launch day was acting up even worseExpect not to be able to play whenever Ubisoft launches a new titleOverall:I really wanted to like this game since I'm such a huge RPG fan, but this felt as if it was designed for children. They released a patch within the month after release to fix some of the launch day bugs, but I never got to experience the game with that patch.EDIT: Also, last time I buy anything from Ubisoft before its on sale, this game has been out less than 2 months and it's already 25% off, with all DLC being 40%. Its akin to a slap in the face to those who pre-ordered or bought it when it was released. I rarely pre-order or buy during opening month, forever Transistor gave me a hungering for RPGs that could not be satiated so that's why I picked this up."
,Recommended,256290,20695559,"Posted: 23 January, 2016",all,dangerhighdoltage,"Funshine Bear was hurtling towards my screen with sniper precision. My 7-year old daughter is a stuffed toy-throwing expert. She *really* fell in love with the lead heroine, Aurora, and each dramatic encounter would leave her aghast as the story unfolded. In this case a plushie bear attack was warranted as Child of Light got real right there. Funshine Bear might have lost a bit of stuffing too. The game was my choice for our daddy-daughter gaming nights and we enjoyed it so much, it warranted two playthroughs.Upon first firing up the game, what immediately hits you will be the gorgeous artwork and orchestral music.  It grabs you by the arm and just fills your senses with a massive serotonin hit. Backgrounds are exquisitely crafted with several motifs ranging from grey-blue ghostly forests to lava-filled mountain passageways in the belly of a giant colossus.  Scene by scene, level by level, you will experience lush hand-drawn imagery and meticulously crafted character art design. Each level has it's own art tone, much like a watercolor painting that conveys emotion and depth.  Also, the characters you encounter have an amazing originality and natural warmth in their faces.  You'll easily be able to recall them even months after you complete the game.  Honestly, Child of Light has some of the most beautiful art direction I have ever seen.  At no point in the game does this attention to detail falter. It is consistently gorgeous with an air of childhood fantasy accentuated by it's unforgettable theme song.Then there is the story and dialogue, done entirely in iambic pentameter.  Which to some may be annoying, but I personally found it to be an amazing surprise.  My 7-year old followed it a bit more easily than some other games and the rhyming conveyed that fairytale vibe you'd expect.  I will say that after awhile, you do encounter some odd dialogue that either barely makes sense or doesn't seem to rhyme as well as other passages.  While it's not a major issue, sometimes I didn't quite follow what was being explained.  Doing an entire game in iambic pentameter is no easy task, so having a few odd bits here and there didn't really affect my enjoyment.The story follows a little princess from a kingdom in Austria that either died or mysteriously ended up in a mystical land called Lemuria.  I couldn't really follow how in the world she got to Lemuria, but almost all the story takes place there except for a few cut scenes of her father.  You explore and fight, gaining skills and friends who join your party along the way.  Each character is from a chapter in the story such as wizard villagers, giant mice with superb financial skills, an acrobat circus girl and her whiney missing brother, a giant soldier dude who seriously needs a manicure, and a young fish girl who probably has the coolest attack of all by knocking her opponents backwards to gain an attack advantage.  Boss battles tend to be tentacled monstrosities or evil villains turned into aquatic-looking baddies with minions.  You attack the tentacles or minions, but it's best to get the head as much as possible and don't bother to use any potions or life saves until the last few bosses because you will seriously need them then and only then.Gameplay consists of a really interesting blend of crafting gems for skill points, a time limited RPG attack system, and a very nice method of switching party members to change up the strategy.  It works quite well.  The fighting occurs along a time line, giving you some unique methods of attack and defending.  The gems can be used to help against evil monsters by bolstering your character powers with skill against certain elements such as fire, earth, water, or lightning.  However, if you are familiar with turn based combat, I'd suggest playing on the hardest level.  Eventually, you'll fall in a groove of picking the right set of persons to attack and the right partner to heal them regularly.  I'm not particularly good at turn based combat, but I didn't die until the last few boss battles.  Even my 7 year old girl was able to handle the majority of fights after she saw the way I beat them, and pretty much only asked for help with the bosses when she played by herself on the second playthrough.  It's a little too easy on the normal setting.  You'll have to play with the character selection a bit to figure out which one has the best attack, but other than that it's fairly straightforward.It's quite hard for me to critique this game, it has so many positives going for it.  Could it be a little less fairytale-ish? Um, yeah.  It could, but in doing so it loses some of that charm it's shooting for.  Was the combat boring? Not at all, occasionally tedious at worst.  With all the options given to you there is a lot to play around with in attacks and strategy.  Knock an enemy back in the timeline, defend until the right moment, switch out a character at the last moment, use the little firefly to slow down the enemy attack.  I could go on and on.  Do I really want to play a game about a little girl?  At first, not really.  Then as I played on I began to enjoy it quite a bit.  Child of Light has some of the best style, art, story, music, characters, and combat for such a small title.  I think the only weak link were some of the puzzles which were all on the easy side.  There were a few side quests to do, but I only did half of them.  It was preferable to enjoy the game story and combat rather look around for quests to complete.  This game shines brightly and is well worth the time to finish to the end. I highly recommend it"
