,Not Recommended,256290,30642205,Posted: 20 March,all,Xuchilbara,"Yet another game for which I wished there was a ""neutral"" review option. Child of Light is not a bad game, however it has many little defects that prevent it from being the real gem it could have been. I'll briefly explain what are the pros and cons of the game in my opinion.PROs:+ Beautiful visual style and art direction.+ Simple but effective combat system, which is an interesting variation of the classic ATB-based system often seen in JRPGs like Final Fantasy; the player has the possibility to influence in real time the speed of his enemies, thus making combat more dynamic.+ Tactical boss battles; bosses are pretty smart and strong and you'll need to plan your moves carefully when facing them if you don't want to be defeated, especially when playing at the higher difficulty.+ Good variety of playable characters and skills.+ Nice soundtrack.CONs:- You can only deploy two characters in battle at a time, which limits a lot strategy and often makes you feel like you have too many characters and too little space. Most boss battles require a continuous change of formation in order to be able to use the proper skills at the proper time, which often leads to waste more turns than necessary.- Some characters are rarely useful and towards the end of the game you'll pretty much always use the same ones.- The game is fairly short for an RPG (the 20+ hours I've spent on it were way more than enough to finish it, and I lost a good amount of time trying to farm gems and exp until I got bored) and there's no real need to exp your characters to the full extent of their skill trees in order to progress. There's also no real need to craft all the perfect gems to be equipped, also because finding all the necessary ones would require a lot of grinding. The longevity can be extended by playing a New Game+ but since there's no real change or reward for doing it, most people won't bother.- The story is very basic, despite the interesting presentation and the peculiar rhymed narration, and that's just awful for a RPG like this. Yes, there is some lore (god I'm starting to hate this word) to be reconstructed by finding confessions, but it's nothing particularly detailed or deep. Most of the backstory is left to the imagination and all focus is on the simple main plot.- Not a defect of the game itself, but it requires a Uplay account to be played. It wasn't a problem for me to create one but I really find stupid to use two DRMs for a single game. If Ubisoft didn't want people to play this anywhere else than on their platform, they shouldn't have allowed Valve to sell it on Steam. Period.Considering all I think that Child of Light is a flawed little gem that could be worth a play but only if picked at sale price and only if you're not looking for deep gameplay or story. Otherwise you'll be very disappointed. I honestly expected much more from this title considering its fame and the enthusiastic reviews, but I guess that nowadays people are just too much inclined to see all the positive aspects of something they knee-jerk like and forget about objectivity."
