,Recommended,256290,10226401,"Posted: 24 May, 2014",all,Bombadil,"I've played the entire game through twice now, and I feel comfortable in saying that, on the whole, I would recommend Child of Light to anyone who asked. But that doesn't mean it's without major flaws. As much as I enjoyed playing the game, the longer I did so, the more I became convinced of one thing: Child of Light is a decent game that could’ve been a GREAT game with better story and character development.Before I further explain that thought, let me leave you with a list of things I really, really liked about Child of Light (in no particular order):1. Aurora. Despite my (soon-to-be-explained) issues with the character development, I enjoyed playing her because she’s a character with real agency. Over the course of the game, she makes a series of tough decisions using her own intuition and courage, and the narrative never treats her with condescension, or undermines her ability to make those choices.2. The combat system. This is one of my favorite parts of the game. It’s a classic RPG turn-based system with nifty little twists. Your party members and the enemies appear on a single timeline at the bottom of the screen; the speed at which each character reaches the end of the timeline determines who attacks when. The nifty part is that the player can slow down the enemies’ progress on the timeline—and even interrupt their attacks—thus adding an extra layer of strategy.3. The variety in party members. There are a lot of characters who join your party over the course of the game, and they each have different strengths. This gives you plenty of options in battle, and you can customize your combat style to suit particular enemies. As an added bonus, you can easily swap out party members in the middle of a battle and still have the newly-swapped-in party member attack on the same turn. I was really thrilled about that. More skilled gamers than I might find it too easy, but I enjoyed it. It actually gives you a chance to try out all these characters that you otherwise might never play.4. This is rather an obvious point, but the art. The visuals are simply stunning in this game. There’s so much visual depth to appreciate--I wondered if the art-style would make the background look flat and obviously one-dimensional, but it doesn't at all. The artists and developers also did a good job of integrating the moving characters into the painted scenery. They don’t look disparate or disjointed. It’s all very cohesive and lovely.5. Exploring the world. In large part because of the gorgeous art, it’s really fun to just fly around and look. I liked poking around all the areas of the game and soaking it in.6. (I'm sorry, I must all caps this because I WAS SO HAPPY ABOUT IT.) YOU CAN FLY FOR AS LONG AS YOU WANT WITH NO STUPID, HALF♥♥♥♥♥♥♥ IMPOSED LIMITS.7. The hints and undertones of myth. This is another element I wish had been better developed, but what information we do get about the world’s history and legend is intriquing to me. It creates a nice ambiance, even if it isn't as prominent or developed as I would've liked.So, bearing in mind all the things this game does really well… I have to say, I was fairly disappointed in the storyline and the character development. Those are the two great weaknesses of Child of Light, and I think that's worth knowing before purchasing the game.The story’s greatest shortcoming is its pacing. It starts off interesting enough—the main character, Aurora, appears to die in “the real world” and then wakes up in Lemuria, a fairytale world—and she spends the rest of the game trying to get back home. The pacing is fine in the beginning of the game (central conflict is established), and stays fine toward the middle of the game (central conflict gets more complicated) … but then the “middle” of the game suddenly becomes the end of the game; in what I honest-to-goodness thought was the middle of the story, the end-stage of the story came hurtling at me, and I found myself fighting the final boss, and everything was wrapped up in ten to fifteen minutes. As a player, I was left wondering what the hell just happened (wasn’t I just in the middle of a quest? Shouldn’t there have been more conflict before THE FINAL CONFLICT?). The ending is very, very rushed and therefore feels very, very forced.  I seriously thought I was still in the middle of the story when I came to what was obviously the final dungeon—that’s the kind of rushed I’m talking about.If I had to break it down, I’d say 60% of the game is decently paced, but that last 40%—the part of the story that should feel EARNED, that should be a natural progression of what comes before it—is like a freaking whirlwind. There’s so much wasted potential in the narrative. And that’s the most disappointing part: if the writers/developers had invested more time in developing the middle-end and end of the story, it could’ve been so great. It had all the potential in the world, and then wham. Here’s your hat and coat, show’s over ladies and gentlemen.I think the poor character development goes hand-in-hand with the rushed story. If the narrative had been better-developed, I imagine the characters would’ve been better-developed too. As it is, they get left behind with the rest of the game's potential. The other major flaw with character development is that the writers told rather than showed. Most of what passed for development in the side characters—hints at personal back story and motives for joining the party—are all told rather baldly in dialogue, and that’s it. What you’re told is precisely and only what you get. There’s some cute dialogue between the various characters, but it’s all very surface-level and never leads anywhere significant. There’s no conflict or independent action or progression with them. This is the down side to an item on my pro list: because there are so many party members, none of them get the time and attention needed for real development.The most developed character is Aurora, but her character arc has a lot of the aforementioned problems. I will say, though, that she has more urgency in her story—she has something very real to lose, and that creates organic conflict around her choices and actions. So I do applaud that part of her development—it just could’ve been SO much better with the right pacing.So there you go. This game does a lot of things right, but because of its bad pacing, it really suffers in the story and character department. Ultimately, I enjoyed my experience playing the game, but if a haphazard ending will ruin the experience for you, it might be better to walk away."
76561198052983021,Recommended,256290,10193318,"Posted: 21 May, 2014",all,jvgocavs_2000,"What a wonderful game child of light is.  Beautiful 2d water color graphics pop out at you constantly depicting a dreary forest, and ancient monastery, a mountain mouse village and many other vibrant story book places you will visit on your journey.  The combat is rather simplistic turn based affair, think old school final fantasy except you have a gauge at the bottom of the screen that determines your attack time and you can use a particular friendly ally and some various skills to manipulate it in your favor.  There are many magical and physical attack skills to learn as you level up, giving you some customization and control over your party.  There is also a deep crafting where you build magic stones and charms to power up your equipment.  Lots of interesting characters to meet and some will even join you on your journey to reunite your family.  Best of all every party member you get has a particular style of play so strategy comes in as to who you play when, and you can swap them in and out during battle.  Lots of side quests and nooks and crannies to explore, if you are a completionist or just like to peer in every corner of the world you will be rewarded.  Just enough of a challenge on normal, more experienced RPGers should skip to hard.  One of the better turn based rpgs in a long while, a must play for rpg fans and anyone seeking a whimsical adventure."
