76561198058579678,Recommended,256290,13181382,"Posted: 1 December, 2014",all,Gus123456789,"Child of Light is a bit of a rarety on steam, for several reasons.1st, it needs you to install some third party pseudo platform from ubisoft. If that's a sticking point for you then don't read any more, because the rest of the review is quite positive.2nd, its kinda in the realm of a visual novel, but without any of the drag along standards that keep visual novels geared towards older teens. If you want a story driven game that you could relax while letting your kid brother play at your grandma's house, here you have one.3rd, this is a short and easy game. Not that this is bad, just different. None of that ""Hours into a dungeon and still no save point."" The whole game took me just over 12 hours on casual setting. There is something to be said for an easy dungeon that is just long enough to chew that last piece of rhyming dialogue, before the next one.Graphics are top notch, though it is getting rare to see a new game that graphics aren't awesome in. Still worth mentioning, because its not about detailed realistic graphics that a hudred people coded together in a secret room any more. Instead what makes graphics shine is grabbing onto an artistic vision and being true to it throughout the game, which Child of Light definitely does gorgeously.The music is okay, at least what there is of it. It felt a couple of times like they ran out of funding for their orchestra only 30% through the recordings. Some silence here and there, and a couple of somewhat obvious loops.Personally, I very much enjoyed this game. I really hope to encounter not a sequel, but a series of games based on this style.Here are the subjective numbers:10/10 graphics4/10 music and sound9/10 story0/10 first person shooter experience8/10 game experience10/10 storybook experience"
,Recommended,256290,12103171,"Posted: 14 September, 2014",all,emil_hedgehog,"An RPG with a beautiful watercolour artstyle and a lovely soundtrack to boot. The difference between this game and other turn-based RPGs is that each character's move is set on a timeline, with the player having the ability to slow the speed of each enemy's move, creating a more tactical approach to fighting than just waiting for your next turn to occur. The story is really well set out as well, with a great cast of characters and conversations in the style of poems. The only downside to the game is that you need to run UPlay in order to play it, but if you can overlook that then you'll find a great hidden gem from the past year's games."
