76561198008899722,Recommended,256290,18405970,"Posted: 9 October, 2015",all,DragonsDeck,"Child of Light is a somewhat short but still fun take on the RPG genre.  I played the game on the casual difficulty, there is also an option for hardcore difficulty but I'm not sure what that changes that makes to the gameplay.You start off as a girl named Aurora who begins a journey in another land.  At the start of the game you are only limited to walking along the ground however you will soon be granted the gift of flight and the game takes off from there.  After learning to fly you'll begin exploring the world of Lemuria and gaining companions to explore the world with you and fight the evil your tasked to fight.The combat in the game is active turn based combat with the ability to have your turn or the enemies turn interupted.  There is the waiting phase and the casting phase.  If you attack an enemy in the casting phase they will lose their attack, while if the enemy attacks you in that phase you lose your turn.  There are skills both passive and active (friendly or enemy) that can speed up or slow down your waiting/casting bar.  There are not to many complicated enemies in the game.  Most enemies are pretty easy to decipher what they are weak to (Water/Fire/Lightning/Light) and you are able to slot some gems into your weapons/armour to plan for them.  As well some characters have type specific damge.And moving into Characters.  The game features a wide array of various side kicks to help Aurora in her quest.  The side characters have a unique look and feel to them.  Your elemental light companion will be your main companion through the whole game and does add some uniqueness to the game.  He has the ability to find hidden areas as well as aid in battle or heal Aurora outside of battle.  However when the battles begin is where the most of the characters begin to feel kind of generic.  Most of the characters have very similar abilities outside of a select few.  For the most part they have a single target attack, multi target attack and then a spell of some sort.  For my play through I only used 3 or 4 of I think the 8 avaiilable side characters.  You also gain levels fairly frequently which lets you keep adding to the skill tree.  The skill tree seems large at first, however the amount of levels gained, the tree fills quickly.  But progressing through the skill tree doesn't provide as big a reward as it should, most of it is just increasing damage for certain abilities.The enemies do also fall into the generic sorts in battle.  There isn't the biggest diversity of enemy types and then some are reused for the different element types (Fire/Water/Lightning), but there's enough types you won't see the same ones over and over gain the whole game.The story is good, nothing ground breaking or exremely memorable.  But it does have it's moments that keep you interested in it.The art is probably the biggest thing that I enjoyed about the game.  The game has a very unique/interesting art style and while not everyone may like it, I felt it suits the game's story and overall feel of the game.  There are variety of unique locations in the game and the art does make them feel unique and makes the game enjoyable to explore.The levels/areas in the game are fairly straight forward.  There are some puzzles and hidden areas to find, but for the most part each area is pretty simple and straight forward to go through.  There is a little bit of backtracking throughout the game but not enough that it gets frustratiing.The game is a uPlay activated game and for some that's a big issue.  I've never really had any big issues with uPlay that haven't got resolved quickly.  The game does go on sale fairly frequently and I would suggest picking it up on sale as it is fairly short and not overly difficult.  Also the DLC is not realy required however I did enjoy the Golem so I feel that might be worth picking up with the game.Overall if you are looking for a not to difficult active turn based RPG with unique visuals than this game should meet all those requirements.  If you are looking for a lengthy adventure, or a more challenging task, than this is something you may want to pass over.  I enjoyed the game for what it was and it was enjoyable to play through."
