76561198016308878,Recommended,256290,12504521,"Posted: 15 October, 2014",all,demonborntwice,"As a player of console-style RPGs, I'm really happy this game exists.  It's a beautiful example of how art direction can add so much to solid gameplay and a classic, if well-worn, story.  The game's combat system is really easy for any veteran of the genre (which is why they included a Hard mode), but works well and integrates well into the tactics you can do with your party.  It's solid, it's fun, and it strikes that balance where battles don't frustrate you into hating whenever they crop up, but they also interest you enough to put thought into the fight.It's really the art direction that sells this game, though.  Everything is a dreamy watercolor and ink, perfectly suited for a children's story book.  Coupled with the excellent music, I found myself completely involved in Aurora's adventure, wanting her to succeed and happy that I was there helping her out in a way.  I cringed at her bare feet on the rocky ground, chuckled at every time she had to sternly correct people that she wasn't a princess, smiled at her childish and loving dialogue, fought not to cry at her moment of despair, and sometimes even found myself staring in awe as she took on grim creatures for the sake of Lemuria and her friends.It's a fairy tale, so don't expect any plot twists, but it makes no bones about what it is, and as such people who come in expecting to be sucker-punched should probably stick with the games that do that kind of plot, like OFF or The Witch's House.  This isn't to say that the game lacks emotional torque; I've found it very difficult to get past teary-eyed even at the most intense moments in games I've played, and this thing had me fighting not to cry around the midway point.  I knew every last thing that would happen, and yet the telling was beautiful enough to make it seem fresh and new.  That's the core of it, really; it could have easily fallen apart with how cliched everything could be said to be, but it believes so deeply in its story that I ended up believing too, and that experience is what makes the difference."
,Recommended,256290,10046754,"Posted: 7 May, 2014",all,tzumainn,"I'm not entirely sure what drew me to Child of Light.  Was it the beautiful watercolor art?  The plaintive music?  The little girl that reminded me of my own daughter?  All I can say is that the previews exhibited an intangible quality that made the game one that I had to purchase.First and foremost, Child of Light is a classic fairy tale, told simply and in a straightforward manner.  It is filled with the tropes one might expect - wicked stepmother, lost child, an impossible quest - and is also possessed of the melancholy that the best fairy tales have, a feeling intensified by the haunting flute melody.  This effect is also heightened by the beautiful art direction.  I felt like I was watching a painted book illustration come to life, and when I first started the game, I spent a minute or two just marvelling at the way Aurora's hair swirled as if underwater.Child of Light is also a role-playing game, and although some of its mechanics fall short, the main battle system is wonderfully and unexpectedly engaging.  The basic concept is simple: during combat a single time bar shows who is the next to act, whether it be a member of your party or a monster.  Chosen actions and haste attributes affect how long it takes to reach the end of the bar and perform your action.  And if you hit a monster (or vice versa) in the small space of time right before it acts, you interrupt the creature and send it flying back down the time bar.This one modification to a pretty standard combat system adds a layer of excitement and calculation.  Chain-interrupting a monster over and over again feels utterly dominating; trying to ensure that your party avoids interruption can be nerve-wrackingly tense.  And when you encounter later monsters and bosses that punish you for interrupting them, the sudden scramble to figure out an appropriate strategy is enjoyably frenetic.The supporting game systems - skill trees, potions, gem crafting - are less polished, almost like afterthoughts.  Rather than enhancing the play, they feel like something tacked on just to give the player additional things to do.  That leads to another potential criticism: Child of Light is not the most difficult game, and someone yearning for challenging depth may be disappointed.Add my feeling that the ending was a bit abrupt, and the conclusion is that Child of Light could have done with a few more coats of polish.  That being said, I still loved my time playing the game, the sensation of falling from the present into a magical and wondrous world.  For me, Child of Light is an easy game to recommend.--- Closing Eyes is Magic ---""Ready?"" he asks, and Melly nods.  He pinches a blue plastic brick between two fingers and lifts it up before his daughter.  ""And now,"" he says, ""I will make this disappear!""  Melly nods again, solemn as a statue.  She doesn't smile much, not anymore, but he is hopeful that this will do the trick.He holds the brick for a heartbeat longer.  Then he takes his other hand and swirls it.  ""Abracadabra,"" he says.  ""Hocus pocus. . .  Nowclose your eyes!""Melly does so immediately.  A fainttinkfalls somewhere in the room.  ""Look,"" he says.  ""It's gone!""Itisgone.  Melly jumps up and down and claps her hands; pleased, he spreads his arms in triumph.  ""Again!"" she says.  ""Daddy, do it again, please!""He knows he shouldn't, but he no longer has the heart to refuse her much.  And so he does it again: he holds another brick out, he waves his hand, he incants the magic words.  Except this time when he shouts for her to close her eyes, she keeps them open.  Her gaze tracks the brick as he tosses it over his shoulder.He sighs.  ""Potato,"" he says, invoking his pet name for her, ""you didn't close your eyes.""""I wanted to see what you did.""  Melly says.  Her forehead creases, and for a moment he sees the ghost of her mother there.  ""You just threw it!  That's not magic.""He rolls his eyes, exaggerating for effect.  ""Well  of course not.  That's not where the magic is.""  He takes his index finger and places it on her forehead, firmly.  ""Closing eyes is magic.""Melly hesitates, then agrees.  And when he performs the trick a third time, she closes her eyes.  When she opens them, the brick is gone, he is grinning, and she laughs and laughs and laughs.***The next afternoon as they walk home from kindergarten, Melly trips over cracks, stumbles over rocks, bumps into mailboxes.  After the third time she falls, he examines her and frowns.  ""Potato,"" he says, ""are you walking with your eyes closed?""Melly smiles.  One hand grips her father's; the other is outstretched, palm up with fingers lightly curled, as if holding an invisible hand, or perhaps one that has been missing for the past half year.  ""Closing eyes is magic,"" she says, gently.  ""I remembered.""Startled, he opens his mouth.  He should say something, but he does not know what.  So instead he watches his daughter float along, a dream on her face.  A few steps later, he closes his own eyes.  And then he opens them again to cross the street."
