76561198042979946,Recommended,256290,19325720,"Posted: 27 November, 2015",all,achronos0,"It really is a poem, a beautiful, playable poem.If you tend to love games for originality, or for the strength of the theme/mood they create, then you will probably love it.Wonderful art and music and a simple but haunting story combine to evoke a unique mood in Child of Light: childlike wonder coupled with world-weary sadness.The story is simple -- even basic -- but touching and original, and with lots of embellishments to add depth to the world without taking away from the core narrative.Gameplay is enjoyable. It's a fairly simple platformer that becomes a turn-based non-tactical JRPG for combat.It is not hugely difficult, don't expect either the platforming or the combat to be intensely challenging. But I found it very satistfying, and it definitely does its primary job of furthering the mood and the story.Also an aside: almost all of the negative reviews are people complaining about UPlay, not the game -- and many of them just hate UPlay in principle, they aren't even complaining about a specific problem they had with this title.If you factor out the people who just don't like UPlay the approval rating is probably something like 97% or 98%."
76561198069678381,Not Recommended,256290,13311399,"Posted: 10 December, 2014",all,RootBot,"I was first attracted to this game by its unique art style, but I wasn't expecting a game that was more art piece than RPG. This in essence is what the game is. That isn't to say it doesn't do that extremely well. From the music to artistry and even the ham-fisted rhyming dialogue the game is extremely beautiful to look at. The game mechanics just are not there to back it all up. The leveling trees are much too linear and allow for little to no specialization. You will also get many characters to use in the game, but it comes to a point where you will only focus on a core group. If you’re looking for a game that will hold your interest it just isn’t this."
