76561198008710158,Recommended,256290,22046588,"Posted: 25 March, 2016",all,Nostrovelle,"I picked this up today in the sale and so have barely even started, but I feel compelled to write a review anyway. If you haven't played it, I STRONGLY recommend that you do so. I'm only about an hour into it (up to just beyond the first boss) and I'm already spellbound. It's like a fairytale/Disney movie. The video sequences are all told via beautiful stained-glass scenes (remember the intro to Beauty And The Beast, or Sleeping Beauty? That.) The dialogue is often in rhyming couplets, which lends to the fairytale charm of the game. And don't get me started on the hand-drawn backgrounds or the music. Oh my God, the music. Outside of the Final Fantasy series, this is fast becoming my favourite soundtrack. Speaking of Final Fantasy, the combat is very similar in the sense that it is turn-based, dependant on speed - which I adore. I love the idea of the plot (the sun, moon and stars have been stolen and it's up to you to recover them - fantasy plots are my favourites.) Outside of combat, the game is played via side-scrolling environments. Everything just looks FANTASTIC. It lends further belief to the ""games are art"" ideology.I got this for just under £3. If you can get it that cheap for yourself, it's a no-brainer. If I'd known it was this great I would have got it a lot sooner, and happily paid the full price."
