,Recommended,256290,21312265,"Posted: 18 February, 2016",all,Nintendeaux,"Having previously played this on Wii U, I decided to buy this on sale and see what the PC version offered.For the record: I do not hate uPlay. If you are an uPlay hater... well, hate away, you will not find that here. However, you will be unable to play the game if an uPlay update is available. And since my internet stinks, waiting for an update that takes about 27 minutes to complete is a pain. At least on the Wii U I can click, ""Start Software"" while an update is downloading. No such luck on this, so if you have slow internet, be weary. The updates are far and few between, but they are there.Child of Light is a turn-based RPG. It's fun. It's engrossing. It's gorgeous. And the music is just amazing throughout. I will focus the bulk of this review on the turn-based element as it is essential to playing the game and completing all tasks ahead of you.Yes, you have a main quest, but along the way, you find that your friends have problems of their own and you will need to venture off and solve their problems, too. Do not worry, the story does not usually stray from stronger monsters, so you are usually well-matched.You control two characters at a time, which is a little few considering most people enjoy the four-player turn-based times of old. Do not be discouraged, as you can swap on the fly both characters, as long as it is their turn. So if you are low on health or lack the protection from the element your current enemy dishes out, you are able to switch to another character and start anew on that turn.NOTE: If you are in the 'wait-window' (where you are about to act out your play decision for that character), your new swap-in will go back to the beginning of that wait line (not the beginning of the turn) and depending on their overall speed, perhaps a little further back from the line. You won't necessarily lose a lot of time for that turn, but you will not come in mid-stroke and deliver a promising blow. If an enemy is between the wait line and where your previous character sat, it will go before your new arrival takes action.Your characters do not equip armor or anything, this is supplemented by Oculi, small gems. These can be combined three at a time to make a stronger version of itself. You equip one on your weapon, your clothing or your timeline. On your weapon you can gain elemental damage, the higher version the gem, the more percentage the damage and sometimes a combat action effect like paralysis. Same for your clothing, however, it is for elemental protection and defense effects like +EXP bonus or a +ALL Element protection or physical/magical defense across the board. The timeline connection brings to fruition +Evasion while casting, +Interruption of enemy in Wait status, +Stats, +Casting Speed and a good one, dtarting on the timeline further out than normal.These oculi are few in the first six chapters, so you will bounce between three or four main characters at first, until you can get more in the end-game for flexing your strategy. Do not let this discourage you though, between every battle you can switch the oculi to whomever you want and the process is a speedy one. And uPlay even lets you buy more through their reward process if you want to spend some uPlay credits (although I did not take this route, and probably will not).If you try to stick to the same two characters, you will find it far more difficult to proceed after Chapter 6. Up until then you will be okay and will be able to mix and match and learn each characters strengths and weaknesses. Each character is diverse. You will not find any two alike but in a way or three. Take Aurora for instance, she can heal, but she cannot revive like Rubella. Aurora has Starlight, effective against Dark, but only Finn has elemental damage against the other elements. Unless of course you use oculi on another characters weapon, but even then the damage will be far less than Finn's magical prowess.It's good stuff. This game shines in the dark. I thoroughly enjoyed it on both Wii U and here on PC.Now all that aside, you will still find fun collecting the stardust (permanent stat increase), potions, oculi and confessions (notes to bring light to some lore) scattered across the land. But be prepared to fight. To get everything this game has to offer, you will need to master the combat mechanic and lay waste to many an enemy. It is a good thing all characters level-up together so you will not have to gather clean-up experience later because you will be able to switch your characters and oculi throughout and build a strategy worthy of your name."
