,Recommended,256290,29234420,Posted: 13 January,all,avocadoshake,"In ‘Child of Light’, you play as a young girl named Aurora, who one day falls asleep and dies. She finds herself in a strange land called Lemuria, which she finds is cast in darkness by her stepmother Umbra. Aurora then embarks on a quest to find the sun, moon, and stars to restore light to the land of Lemuria. On your quest, you meet a firefly named Igniculus, who becomes your main sidekick in your journey across Lemuria. You also meet a number Lemurians from different factions, some of whom eventually join your party for different reasons. You traverse the game world in a side-scrolling manner, and combat creatures of the dark in a hybrid turn-based/real-time system. You progress in the game by discovering new areas and leveling up Aurora and the characters you meet along the way in an RPG fashion.The game was very enjoyable to play, since I found both the combat and crafting systems very easy to pick up. The combat system was easy to understand, but may take a while to master. You will need to utilize your sidekick Igniculus well to ensure you get the edge in battles. I played the game on Normal mode and found the game sufficiently difficult, since I didn’t try to grind the leveling up of my characters. The ability to choose your battles definitely helped in this regard, and allowed me to focus on other aspects in the game, like the story and the artwork. The crafting system was straightforward, and the buffs offered to your party members were easy to keep track of. For game completionists, there are side quests that you can complete and collectibles to, well, collect, that will keep you occupied with ‘Child of Light’ longer than what the main quest alone can offer. The side quests are short and give life to the NPCs you encounter. The collectibles give you a reason to explore the nooks and crannies of Lemuria’s regions.In terms of the game’s aesthetics - the art design lends to a dreamy, picture book-esque atmosphere. Despite this though, stages and enemies can evoke the haunting and eerie. The soundtrack in general was very pleasant and relaxing to listen to, and reminded me of the tiny music boxes that you play by turning the crank. The use of piano added a melancholic touch to the music. The music during boss fights added a lot to the tension and excitement, therefore making boss fights feel more ‘epic’.‘Child of Light’ was good, but was not without its faults. One of the things that I felt didn’t shine so much was the dialogue. Throughout the game, expect to read dialogue that rhymes, or written in poetry-like manner. At times, the rhymes felt forced, and therefore awkward to read. Another thing that I felt was quite weak was the fleshing out of the characters that join your party. Because of the scant glimpses offered on each character’s history, I didn’t get particularly attached to the characters. Interestingly as well, you get a character quite late in the game, who I didn’t really get to utilize because I was already invested in the other characters’ abilities. Lastly, the biggest gripe I had with this game was of a technical nature. Unfortunately for me, the game could never close properly via the “Exit to Main Menu” option on the main game screen. Whenever I tried to use this option, my computer would just get stuck on a black screen, which I couldn’t get out of by any means. This meant I had to restart my computer. I eventually found out a way to close the game without needing to restart my computer by pressing Alt + Tab, and then closing the game window from the taskbar.All in all, this was a beautifully made game that I think different types of gamers will enjoy. The simplicity in story, combat, and crafting made the game very enjoyable to play, and the art and sound definitely contributed towards making the game a delightful experience."
