76561198022751934,Recommended,256290,14869451,"Posted: 13 March, 2015",all,Manabender,"FIRST IMPRESSIONS:Nearly all of the game's dialogue (which is primarily text-only, with spoken narration for cutscenes) is in a poetic rhyming format. Personally, I find this quite annoying, and it distracts me from the text's actual content. However, I did find a character (party member, even) that goes out of her way to use a word that does NOT rhyme, when there's a better-fitting word that DOES rhyme, after which another character corrects them. I find this somewhat amusing.The combat, however, piques my interest. First off, it uses a ""turn-time"" system, whereby faster units take more turns than slower ones, as opposed to Pokemon (for example) where speed only determines who moves first in a turn, yet everyone still gets the same number of turns. However, this game takes it a step farther; each unit's turn is split into a wait period and a cast period. Once a unit's wait period finishes, they select an action and proceed to the cast period. Once the cast period is done, the action occurs. However, an action can be interrupted if the unit is hit while in their cast period. This results in a lot of strategy in manipulating the timers, especially given the fact that you can pick an enemy and slow them down nearly any time.I read a lot of reviews that mentioned having problems with Uplay, be it the inabilty to play or having saves erased. I haven't had these issues. I also read that you should use Uplay in offline mode, which I've done thus far.SECOND IMPRESSIONS:Now that I have more than two party members, I now see how party swapping works. It's kind of wierd. At first, I thought it was the same as FF10; on a player unit's turn, you can swap him/her out for any other player unit not already active, and this is completely seamless and takes no time. But there's another option. Lets say you have three party members, named A, B, and C. A is picking an action. B is on the field, but waiting to act. C is off the field. You can use A's action to swap C in for B, and this will cause A's turn to be spent, but C is now immediately ready to act. Confusing? Yeah, I thought so too. As a result, I only use the swap-for-self method that FF10 uses.I'd also like to comment on the art style. It has its own unique fantasy charm. I like to describe it as the developer being onjuuuustthe right amount of drugs.THIRD IMPRESSIONS:Dang, the game is gettinghard.There's two difficulty levels, Casual and Expert. I picked Expert. The difficulty was high, but managable until recently. It's getting quite brutal at this point. I'm managing, but only barely.And I'm loving it.BRING IT ON!"
,Recommended,256290,21115999,"Posted: 10 February, 2016",all,XXXSWAGXXX1337XXX360NOSCOPEXXX,"Warning: Indepth reviewVisuals-Gorgeous watercolor artstyle-Charming/cute fairytale-like character designs-Extremely beautiful and detailed environments and scenery aided by the artstyle-High attention to detail for character/skill animations. E.g, main character fumbles around a lot while wielding/using her sword because it is practically the same size as herAudio-Eargasmic fully orchestrated soundtracks-Music styles range from lighthearted disneylike bgm to intense, adrenaline pumping musical scores to sombre, lonely, melancholic pieces-Soundtracks that play during normal monster battles are so epic that they feel more like final boss battles instead-Much effort and detail put into sound effects for every little thing. E.g., sound of barefeet stepping on wet rock as your character moves around a dark forest, or the metal tinkering sound of the crown when it hits the floorStory-Straight out of a fairytale, but with a slightly dark and gloomy atmosphere replacing the usual happy, uplifting mood found in these type of stories-Some nice plot twists and turn of events that match well with the sorrowful mood of the story, but otherwise, fairly straight forward like most fairytales-despite the generally sombre feeling of the story, still heartwarming at times-At its core, a coming-of-age story. People looking for something with an intricate and deep plot will be disappointedCharacters-With the plot being reminiscent of a disney movie, likewise the characters also follow suit (talking animals/ mythological creatures)-Charming/cute characters that compliment each other well due to their distinctive personalities and character traits-Main character (Aurora)  is an incredibly cute and sweet, but brave little girl. (Very likeable protagonist)Dialogue-Everything is spoken in rhymes; adds to the cuteness/fairytaleness of the story, but may become annoying for some people as the game progressesGameplay-Old school turn based combat with several added twists-Order of turns in combat dictated by a timeline mechanic, which is further influenced by an interruption mechanic when characters are attacked during the 'casting' part of the timeline-Timeline/interruption/cursor mechanic help add to the tension/unpredictability of fights and fosters strategic elements unique to these mechanics (e.g, knowing when it is worth using weak, but fast speed attacks to interrupt enemies VS straight brute force killing the monsters with strong but long cast time spells)-However, at its heart, it is still turn based battle, so it will not appeal to all people despite the previously mentioned mechanics that speed up the flow of battleRecommend to everyone but the most diehard haters of turn-based battle.Oh, and theres Uplay. ♥♥♥♥ Uplay.But seriously though, it's worth the hassel of installing and signing up for Uplay to experience this game. Cheers~"
76561198154912826,Recommended,256290,20322736,"Posted: 5 January, 2016",all,ADRNTESPDR,"I love turn based RPG's and Child of Light delivers a satisfying system encouraging strategy and diligence. It's simple, but as the plot progresses you need to employ new strategies and be smarter to keep up with new enemy variants. Child of Light is addicting and entices exploration. It's not far into the game that you gain a new power to roam around with which makes the game much more enjoyable and opens up the 2D map extensively to reveal a much larger world than you realized. Playing alone is fun in itself, but one of my favorite features in Child of Light is the cooperative mechanic that allows for another person to join in to help explore and fight through use of the mouse. Cooperative play adds a whole new element of teamwork as your partner can use the mouse to heal the party or slow enemies while you plan the next move.The story and presentation of Child of Light is charmingly reminiscent of a classic Disney movie. The journey of Princess Aurora as she finds her way through a magical woods to find a way to save her father, while not breaking ground in storytelling, has that classic fairytale vibe that harkens the mind to more innocent and simple times. As you journey through the woods you'll come across several companions to join your party. While the cast of characters is diverse and their interactions amusing, you'll find yourself using only a couple through the length of the game--bringing an additional one or two out to deal with certain enemy types. This didn't really bother me, but it's to be expected when you have this many characters in your party in such a short game.I suppose that's my only gripe with Child of Light--it felt short, but that may be because a friend and I beat it in the length of a day. I got it on sale and don't regret what I payed, but I can't help but feel thankful I didn't pay full price. Regardless, I had a blast exploring and fighting bosses with my friend. If you like RPG's with turn-based battle mechanics or a story that harkens back to the classic Disney Princess tales of yore, then you will enjoy Child of Light."
,Recommended,256290,16873000,"Posted: 3 July, 2015",all,Waffle King,"White Kid-An Official Waffle King Review~Find morehere.Roses are red.So is cherry pie.Better bite the pillow.Because I'm going in dry.Haha, see, I'm a poet. I shouldn't be writing stupid reviews with my poetic style. I should write children's fairy-tales. If Ubisoft can do it with Child of Light, why can't I? I can rhyme better than Black Mother Goose. Also known as Big Mama G. It's a thing, really. What else do you think black children get read to them before bed?Their rights.I mean, Child of Light is a pretty good game. Beautiful, fun to play, and is pretty artsy if you consider that Ubisoft is French. I mean, since when does France know a thing about art? Their idea of art is a black and white movie about a red balloon. Psh. But me, I'm just a manifestation of art and poetry. You know?Child of Light is Ubisoft's attempt to make a game with a soul for once. And man, they did a pretty good job. For once. It's available on pretty much every major platform. And to be completely honest, I'd recommend playing on any other besides this one. Uplay is a ♥♥♥♥ing ♥♥♥♥♥. Fantastic game, but Uplay is annoying as♥♥♥♥♥♥Aside from that, Child of Light is a magical experience.This game has NO climbing in it. You can fly, instead.A sort of turn-based RPG featuring a time-based system, very similar to Grandia, Child of Light is trying really hard to be a fairy-tale. It's got the princess, it's got the magic, it's got the evil queen, and it has midgets with beards. The whole shebang.Little princess Aurora goes through a magical portal to Austria, where the game apparently takes place. The magical land of Austria. A land of fantasy and wonder. Too bad Austria is only a fictional world.In Austria, she learns that an evil queen has stolen all the light of the world. There is only darkness now. Light is the good guy. Darkness is the bad guy.Because white is good and black is bad.Because white means purity and goodness, and black means evil and unemployment. And gang violence.You'll fly through the fantasy world of Austria, fighting the creatures of darkness. The world is flat and 2-D, and layered with beautiful hand-drawn environments. It's an incredibly pretty game. Those Frenchmen might not be able to win wars, but damn. They're really good at drawing.The combat system is actually pretty complex. There's a sort of time meter that small icons representing characters will move along. They move at different speeds depending on the character's stats, and all race to hit an action point. At that point, they can choose what move to use or what action to take. However, as they move along the action meter to charge up for that action, getting attacked will interrupt their move and send them back on the time meter.You can only have two characters out at a time, but swapping them doesn't count as an action. If you swap out your magic user for your healer, they start at the point the other character left at. However, that does then open up weaker characters like supporters to attacks.It's basically a game of juggling, trying to interrupt your enemies and swap out allies at the right moments to control the flow of battle. Not as easy as it sounds, as certain enemies can counter interruption and other moves. You'll also have to be wary of physical/magical attacks, and different elemental attacks. And especially not as easy as it sounds because I ♥♥♥♥ing suck at juggling.Controlling the flow of battle is the most important aspect of the game. And lucky for you, there's a slightly more direct way to manipulate it. You have a little firefly companion that can do little but shine light. But that light can slow down enemies, stun them before you run into them, and open special chests and such on the map. And during combat he can be used to influence the flow of battle quite a bit. Slowing down enemies just enough to interrupt them, or using his light to heal allies before they die. Normally he's controlled by player one, but if you're playing on Wii U he can be used by a second player with a Wii Remote Super Mario Galaxy style. A great way to get Grandma in on the action.While the combat system itself is smooth and flows great, other areas of the battle system aren't so smooth.Namely, the equipment system. You'll equip your characters with different colored gems called ""Oculi"". Why they called them Oculi, I think it was just to make something rhyme somewhere that they couldn't find a good rhyme to.Oculi have different properties, and bestow all sorts of powers and stat boosts depending on what it is and how it's equipped. They can be fused to craft stronger ones, or special ones. Or strong special ones.A great concept, however the execution was sloppy and clunky. Whenever I got new gems I'd loathe going to equip them. It was a long process. An ordeal.The gems you have equipped are not present in your crafting menu. Meaning to make use of gems, you need to unequip everything from everyone, craft gems, and then reequip everything to everyone. It's just annoying and frustrating, to the point where I'd avoid crafting gems for as long as I could. Which is sad, because the system itself is actually pretty cool.The Oculi system is but a burnt croissant on the face of France, however. It's the only real drawback in an otherwise beautiful game.The story can be pretty simplistic, but it's supposed to be a fairy-tale. And its dialogue is incredibly corny, because everything is forced to rhyme... but again, it's supposed to be a fairy-tale. They were purposeful design choices. To make the game cheesy. You know how much the French love their cheese. It's not really that bad... but it's kinda cringey at times. Depending on your lactose tolerance, it may or may not be that bad of an issue.But aside from being cheesy and having an♥♥♥♥♥equipment system, it's a fantastic game and a great addition to the Wii U's lacking RPG library. Not only is it fun with solid mechanics, but it's stylized beautifully. The art style and music really deliver a memorable experience.The style is great, and they put so much effort into giving the game a heart and soul. Which begs the question, why can't Ubisoft do this more often?Not every game has to be a AAA franchise entry with guns and climbing and half♥♥♥♥♥♥♥stealth mechanics. White people that can climb has been done so many times, you know?I mean, the princess in this game is white too. But she FLIES.That's a whole different genre.If big budget game companies could learn that not everything is a AAA game that needs to be ♥♥♥♥♥d out into a franchise, maybe we could see more games like this made.CHILD OF LIGHT 2: REVELATIONS: BLACKLIST_FLAG_DOGS: ORIGINSLIKE ASSASSIN'S CREED WITH GUNS"
