,Recommended,256290,18393389,"Posted: 9 October, 2015",all,x0nex,"*This game requires Uplay third party downloaded.**I played this on another account, so my hours on Steam aren't accurate.*Level0ne CuratorChild of LightScoreCommentsGameplay7The controls of Child of Light were fair but felt clunky as a platformer. Flying was fun until I had to navigate smaller spaces, in which I found I was often crashing the sides and hurting myself. I didn’t so much enjoy the battles, as they got a bit repetitive. It's a platformer with RPG stats, but I found I wasn't interested in the stats. Also the Oculli crafting system felt rushed with some chance buffs not that helpful in battle.Story8I liked moments of the story, but wasn’t completely enthralled. I liked the idea of the story being told in a rhyme, but eventually I was cringing at it. Perhaps a better story could’ve been told without the nursery rhymes constricting it.Graphics10I really enjoyed the graphics of Child of Light. I found it was beautiful to look at, and while flying around the art and environment was wonderful. It felt very much like a children’s storybook and the art style looked hand painted.Audio9.5I really enjoyed the soundtrack to this game. The music here really set the mood at the appropriate moments. The sounds in the game were fitting and often guided/alerted me when I was begrudgingly entering battle.Replayability3While it was a relatively fun game to play, I can’t see myself continuing to maximize my character’s stats/abilities any further, let alone replaying the game again. With a decent story and gameplay, I have no wishes to return to Lemuria.Overall7.5Child of Light set me in a beautiful place called Lemuria. The music added to the tranquil beauty. But the controls felt awkward at times, though didn’t hinder me too much. I want to love the story, but unfortunately I couldn’t get passed the rhyming.More reviews by OneGame Soundtrack on YouTubehttps://www.youtube.com/watch?v=v6KcYN0A5LY"
,Recommended,256290,15609727,"Posted: 29 April, 2015",all,Cerenzio,"Amazeballs, DO play with a second player."
,Recommended,256290,13961006,"Posted: 12 January, 2015",all,TugBoet,"I recommend this game but with a caveat.  Let's get the negative out of the way immediately.Combat.It is an interesting system that has more depth than anticipated and it works very very well for much of the game.  As the difficultly and story progresses you become handcuffed by it.  I believe this could be rectified by allowing for a third friendly combatant even if only for the second act.  Some party members are simply so specialized they are swapped in for one turn then back out but often times this simply serves to extend some of the more lengthy combat segments later in the game.  It nearly soured me on the entire title but the overwhelmingly positive experience in the rest of the game saves that.  Be warned of this, combat will become tedious and repetitive water beats fire, lightning beats water, rock paper scissors gameplay.  The debuff and buff mechanics tend to fall by the wayside do to the need to swap out characters when simply pouring out damage will suffice.  A missed opportunity.Let me cover another aspect of this game that is (for me) a HUGE positive.  If you have small children as I do who constantly want to help and take part in your game time, the ability for a second player to control your firefly companion is amazing.  My kids LOVED lighting him up to heal my fighters or making bad guys duck.  They loved lighting him up to unlock the unfortunately simple puzzles found throughout.  This alone will make me revisit this game over and over in the future.As so many reviewers have mentioned the art, music, and thematic elements are really superb.  It is incredibly easy to dive into this game and become enraptured by your surroundings and the surreal feel of playing through a daydream the game evokes.  That combined with overall solid gameplay and story save it from the somewhat troublesome combat issues mentioned.  It is truly a beautiful and memorable game.  It's style will stay with you for a long time."
