76561198027692026,Not Recommended,256290,27657327,"Posted: 26 November, 2016",all,Jamez,"Child of Light is the indie kid of a company that's used to punch out AAA titles. Having been developed by Ubisoft it had all the funding and manpower of a big gaming company but regarding the success of titles like Limbo and Bastion, the gaming giant fancied a glimpse towards the indie scene. Which is great, because Clild Of Light is pretty awsome in it's own way. It looks and feels like a mobile, touchpad-based game dressed in pc garments. I could never quite shake the feeling off that playing this game with mouse felt awkward and unnatural. I would have wanted to press on the screen, move the characters around with my fingers. And that's really cool as well, because pc and mobile games don't mix that well, they're two different worlds. This kind of adaption adds and extra perspective.DesignThe watercolor world looks gorgeous. I wouldn't say ""original"", because let's be honest: the idea was out there and screaming for someone to pick it up, Ubisoft just happened to be the first one. The main character, Aurora is a distinctive and memorable figure with a striking progression pattern throughout the game which really binds the player emotionally to her.  She has a companion in the form of a glowing blue firefly who adds to good character build and strengthens the feeling that in her hour of need, she's not alone.SoundThe stunning visuals are accompanied by equally beautiful melodic and sombre soundscapes that blend well and deliver just the right kind of moods this kind of fairy tale adventure needs.CombatBattles in this game are executed in an old turn-based RPG boardgame style, with a timer twist. You have a number of fighters to choose between depending on what you want to inflict on the enemy and Aurora's firefly has a strategic role to play in it. Enemies alike come with different stats and powers, pushing the player to build different strategies depending on who you're facing.StoryNone of the characters actually make any sound. The dialogues are presented in written form, giving the impression that it's half fairy tale, half computer game. However, the quality of the dialogues is hectic and much too often working against the game's immersion. Same goes for all the written material found throughout the world of Lemuria. The old dialect used in the game had it's moments, but it really ended as a poor adaption of a great idea.ConsThe game failed pretty badly with the character upgrade system, which felt unexciting and half of the time like chores that you just had to endure though you didn't want to. I didn't feel like there was much difference where I spent my easily earned xp points, they dropped almost after every battle and often just gave the opportunity to boost health points or mana a little bit.The battles will start feeling monotonous very early on. They're not particularly hard, but there's so many of them and they're kind of lengthy and you can't really skip most of them if you want to survive the boss battles. It took quite a lot of will of strenth to advance in the game which resulted in playing the game over a vast period of time - several months came and went before I gathered myself enough to finish it.VerdictIn the end this beautiful thing drowned in humdrum."
