,Recommended,256290,10076573,"Posted: 10 May, 2014",all,Bahuemac,"Outline, Story/Plot, Conclusiveness:Basic, not too special good/light vs evil/dark story.Rather ordinary plot devices and ""messages"". Like a girl growing up on the hardships of her adventure and taking more and more responsibility and that family, friendship and faith can overcome all - ideas I cannot particularily relate to. I believe they are overused in fictional media, and with this lose their appeal and meaningfulness to me. They probably make up some of the most fundamental aspects of life and I can respect if writers actually believe in this, but sometimes this stuff feels pretentious and a bit uninspiring to me.The ending felt a bit rushed. I didn't expect the game to end as early as it did, even though the rough outline and the ""goal"" was foreseeable and the story found a conclusive, logical ending.Voice Acting, Narration, Writing, Music, Sounds:Almost no voice acting. Only a neutral narrator once in a while. The characters in the game only speak via text.Most narration and text is in verses and rhymes. Sometimes it felt a bit forceful, in other instances it helped to give weight to some of the statements Aurora or her companions were giving. All in all I think they did a great job with this and that it helps to create the ambiance of playing a fairytale. It surely wasn't easy to write all this, I suppose, and still have it make sense. I didn't understand it all, as English isn't my main language and I'm not used to poetry of this kind in any of the languages I speak.Nice music and some interesting sound design (Aurora walks on her bare feet, and you can hear this when she touches the ground; I thought the flapping of her wings sounded nice too).Art/Visual Design, Animation:Beautiful level art (resembling watercolor paintings/aquarelle).Somewhat underwhelming character portrait art (looks a bit like something a nonprofessional would put up on deviantART).Nicely animated protagonist. Aurora moves very smoothly, from what I've seen she is a mix of 2D and 3D. Just as some other main characters. Most other people and creatures look entirely 2D to me, and appear less ""plastic"" as a result. It's not easy to explain but best to look at in trailers or the likes.Combat, Difficulty, Skilling, Platforming/Puzzling, Local Co-Op:Turn-based combat. Very unusual for Western games, it's what you see in Japanese RPGs usually. But even Japanese RPGs often appear overly strategic to me with dozens of units to control on a big grid field, or they put you under stress with real-time elements. Child of Light sticks to more traditional RPGs. You control two characters in combat, and fight a maximum of three enemies in turns. There is a turn priority, and there are means to slow down/speed up combatants to get them make their turns more quickly/slowly. You can exchange your fighters freely once it's their turn, and time your attacks to interrupt your enemies' actions.Normal difficulty was pretty easy. If you handle the turn priority system right you can keep your enemies interrupted most of the time, or you kill them quickly enough before they start dealing more damage. Also, there are three ways of healing people (too many, perhaps): Simultaneously to moving Aurora around in the world and choosing fighting orders in combat you control a firefly spirit. This firefly has an energy bar he can exhaust to light up his surrounding area and by that either heal your fighters or blind/slow down enemies. Most damage I was able to heal with this firefly. I almost never used any consumables (healing potions and the likes), and healing spells rarely when the energy bar of the firefly was exhausted. Was someone still hurt too much I exchanged him or her with another fighter. Towards the end of the game you have like 3-5 fighters to choose from, and I rarely saw the health of any of them turn dangerously low.The game is advertised with ""200 skills"" on one of the trailers. But this is a bit eye-washing. There are many skills, but a significant part of them are passive skills which merely increase the attributes of your fighters and not actually give you something to alter your combat experience with. There is not a particulary lack of active skills - there are numerous fighters, and they all have specific, unique and fitting skills designed towards their character profiles and backgrounds, but there is little freedom in developing the characters as there are only two, at best three ""paths"" to move on the skill trees with no way of branching out. You go path A, path B or path C. Inbetween you may stop going one and walk some you previously ignored, and vice versa, but that's about it. Ultimatively they could have given you two or three perfectly flattened left-to-right skill lines for each character instead of the winded ones you find in this game.There is some platforming and puzzling, but it's not really worth mentioning. Spikes coming out of the walls, a few boxes to push on some buttons to open doors. What is interesting is that you can use the already mentioned firefly to pick up items and open chests. It's glowing light is used in several places to activate buttons, solve riddles based on shadowplay and to get past obstacles. It is a form of ""singleplayer co-op"" as I believe this is called, and interestingly strongens the ties between Aurora and the firefly as her constant companion in an active way really feelable by the player. Apparently a second local human player can control the firefly, which may help feel this tie even more so. There sure is a lot of to do with the firefly, so this local 2-player co-op may be a lot of fun (I didn't try it myself)."
