76561198019193223,Recommended,256290,13302004,"Posted: 9 December, 2014",all,Galadhatan,"A lovely game, overall, though it took me a while to get into it. I'm not a fan of the Final Fantasy style fights, but, eh... The game itself is simple enough, with Aurora an exiled girl running and flying around, collecting a band of warriors drawn from the various fantasy races, fighting random evil and exorcising the big baddies. The narrative is fine, and would do better were it not for the horrible doggerel it is written in. It is a problem of good narrative made bad to fit into cramped and unwieldy rhyme: it would have been better to keep a bedtime story style with prose and some couplets at the end of each scene. Dialogue appears between companions at the end of fights (by the end, that is), which was unwelcome, since by that point the various interruptions the game presents tend to add up to a nuisance.For as bad as the rhymes were, though, the graphics were outstanding. Watching Aurora grow and transform is very well done: she is a good character design, and the animations overall (especially of her) are very good. The scenes appear to be hand-drawn, and the addition of Igniculus (the sprite/elemental) creates nice shadow/lighting effects (as well as very important strategies in the fight sequences). The graphics are really what make this game worth playing. The soundtrack, also, is very well produced (I can't confirm, but it seemed to me to be actual orchestral tracks for some of the key melodies). If you can get over the bad verse, you should find this game to be quite enjoyable. 7/10."
,Recommended,256290,13277480,"Posted: 7 December, 2014",all,Wide And Nerdy,"What an enchanting game.It feels like a fairy tale with rpg elements. Like a well illustrated children's storybook come to life in video game form. RPG combat system is classic with a few updates. A lot of the tactical element of the game centers around altering how quickly you or your enemies can attack. If you can attack your enemy when their initiative meter gets into the red zone, you can interrupt them potentially setting them back an entire turn. And you have multiple options for affecting that timing.While your attacks are turn based, you have a fairy companion controlled separately by the mouse who can heal you, or slow down your enemies and operates in real time.  Out of combat this same companion can interact with objects on the map that Aurora can't reach in a variety of ways allowing two people to play, one operating Aurora with the keyboard and the other controlling the fairy with the mouseThe trailers do a pretty good job of letting you know what you're in for and the beauty and grandeur of it all holds up throughout the game. Its proof that you can have a beautiful game without demanding that your video card spit out the maximum number of polygons and photorealistic textures and next gen lighting effects. As shown here, with some actual art direction, you can do so much more with so much less.The story is a basic coming of age tale combined with a heroes journey. Young Princess Aurora seemingly dies in bed only to wake up in a strange new land. Able to see haunting visions of her own father falling ill from grief as he mourns her passing, she must explore her new world and try to find her way home while making friends and enemies along the way.One annoying thing was the decision to write the game in rhyming couplets. I know that this was done to hold with the storybook fairy tale conceit but it started to wear thin for me rather quickly and had me wishing that they'd just speak plainly. But I am a childless 35 year old man (what are you looking at me for? Maybe I want a change of pace from the high octane AAA experience every now and then), so your mileage may vary. I've seen plenty of comments both ways from other people. I will say that if you find the dialog annoying, its usually not terribly essential to read all of it apart from getting side quests and there's not a huge amount of it anyway. The soundtrack and the art still make for a plenty beautiful experience even if the dialog doesn't work for you and the gameplay should be plenty fun for any fan of classic rpg gameplay.But other than that, everything about this game was great. Nice change of pace too. And again speaking as a childless 35 year old man, I found that it didn't get to ""twee"" for me, so if that was a concern for you, don't worry. Its also a short game for those of you who have lives."
,Recommended,256290,10100544,"Posted: 13 May, 2014",all,Qrow Silvermane,"This game is a masterpiece. There is so much detail put into the game in regards to art and gameplay. Even in the very beginning, I noticed various hidden locations that can expound on the gameplay or lore as a whole. Although I've only played this for a solid hour, I can assure you that this game is wonderful. I fully recommend it.The gameplay is very simple from the beginning, and the turn-based battle system is flawless. I enjoy the various strategies I can take in order to attack my opponents faster, defend myself, prevent myself from being interrupted, and etcetera.The artistic side of the game is perhaps the reason why I first took a look at this game. I don't think I can say much about the artwork other than 'Just check it out. This game is beautiful'.Finally, the lore. My God, if you love poetry and a beautiful, enthralling, story-telling game, you are probably in heaven now. The story, so far, is amazing. I anticipate great things when I continue to play it.Child of Light is a 2.5D sidescrolling RPG adventure that follows the story of Aurora when she awakens in the land of Lemuria. The game is beautiful, the gameplay is simple and functional, and the story is fascinating. From the looks of things, this game is a MUST GET. For jut $14.99... there shouldn't be much of a reason why you wouldn't be able to buy Child of Light."
