76561198072263820,Recommended,256290,16367128,"Posted: 13 June, 2015",all,BigBadwolfm4n,It was purty
,Recommended,256290,15620130,"Posted: 30 April, 2015",all,KingofKingz958,"Anticipation can be a double edged sword. You get that stuttering, spine tingling feeling, so excited from the potential of something, but equally fearful because you glimpse something with such promise that you pray for it to live up to it, knowing how many times you’ve been disappointed before. This was the sensation I had when I first heard about Child of Light. Knowing the creators of Far Cry 3 were taking a brief step away from triple-A development to work on a smaller downloadable title sounded improbable, but very exciting.  But once I witnessed the jaw-dropping announcement trailer powered by the same graphical muscle behind the equally gorgeous and flamboyant Rayman Origins and Legends, I was immediately grabbed by the premise. I had my reservations, like my surprise that the publishers of the mega-franchise Assassin’s Creed would green-light this smaller project on a whim and whether the gameplay would eventually be a turn off for me, someone who has played very few JRPG’s. But that’s the incredible thing about Child of Light. It never failed to surprise me.Like a classic bedtime fairy tale, a calming chime and the voice of a whimsical woman heralds us in the opening moments, telling the story of Lemuria and the fall of this prosperous kingdom. A young girl named Aurora mysteriously falls comatose, causing her father to slip into illness from grief. She awakes in a mysterious land and the story begins, Aurora setting out to reunite with her father.The story is wrapped around a layer of iambic pentameter, presenting this almost Shakespearean prose with grace and ambience. Never in a game have I seen the writing take such center stage in the presentation. Whether in the several pre-rendered story cutscenes or traveling around Lemuria, you never go long without another sentimental and enjoyable piece of poetic lyric to accompany your journey. As a lover of well written situational poetry, I love how well the lines sync up with what you are doing at that moment, really adding to my enjoyment. The cast of characters may seem like generic fairy-tale characters, but their personalities were interesting companions for Aurora’s coming-of-age story. With a lovesick mouse, a helpless poetically challenged jester, a cowardly dwarf and more, the cast is colorful and varied, really allowing me to lose myself in this fantasy world. The firefly Igniculus isn’t a standout, but on top of serving numerous gameplay purposes, seems to be rather clueless and curious to aspects of the real human world. Aurora herself seems a bit spoiled at first, but quickly grows into the hero of her story. She helps the citizens of Lemuria, but always stays fixed on her goal of reuniting with her father. Her troubles at the end of the game after taking the whole journey with her made me care about her struggle. While it missed several story opportunities, it still provided a compelling reason to push through to the end.This was where my fears initially began to creep in. As I said, I’m not very familiar with JRPG’s or turn based gameplay in general, but the promise of the game allured me to keep an open mind. Simply put, the gameplay is sublime, simplifying the often-muddled ambiguous speed stats and who attacks first with a simple bar with moving icons on the bottom of the screen. The red end of the bar represents when you can make a move. This bar seamlessly tells you when you can attack and when your opponents can attack, allowing you to make decisions of what action to take. Every action, from using an item to casting spells has a cast time simply laid out from Instant to Very Long. Your opponents speed must be considered with every action, especially since if you are attacked while casting, you are interrupted, canceling your action and sending you further back on the bar. Mix this in with defending, status effects and attacks that hit multiple people at once, and you begin to see how this deceptively simple combat maintains it’s speedy pace and complexity. It’s easy for anyone to pick up, but true masters will learn the speeds of each adversary and know exactly when to interrupt, when to make gutsy plays and when to play it safe. You must always think two steps ahead to maximize your damage and minimize the damage you receive. You can only have two characters out at a time, and while I wished to eventually be allowed to use three, it may have made the game too easy. There are also skill trees and equipable stones to craft and upgrade the abilities of each party member. The skills are pretty varied and useful, but it made me wish for an even greater array of skills to upgrade to, instead of just endlessly upgrading the same abilities.Other aspects of the genre blend perfectly into the overall formula. The game mixes in puzzling and platforming elements as well between fights. The puzzles are simple fun, but won’t really provide much of a challenge. They also lack variety, with puzzles mostly boiling down to pushing blocks on a switch or casting shadows onto walls to open doors and activate objects. You quickly gain the ability to fly, naturally encouraging exploration for hidden items and chests in the sky and underground. Health is a bit too plentiful, but environmental hazards and hidden enemies keep you on your toes frequently. You also have Igniculus, a firefly companion who proves useful throughout the entire game. In combat he can slow down enemies and heal your allies. During exploration and puzzles he can open distant chests, light dark areas, activate switches, as well as letting you get the jump on unsuspecting enemies, yielding positional advantages on the bar for a Surprise Strike. A second player can control Igniculus, but unless you fully cooperate with your partner to maximize his abilities you may be better off by yourself.The gameplay rarely is difficult on Normal difficulty, but on Hard mode even a common enemy can inflict greater damage, with boss battles becoming a thrilling challenge. A New Game + option evens the odds, letting you carry over your stats in a second playthrough.Child of Light is a living, breathing poem and painting, with the soft voice of melancholic, child like wonder bringing you to a different place entirely. The Ubi-Art Framework engine that provided Rayman Legends with such vivid and colorful backgrounds are even more stunning here, with every distant mountaintop, forest, underwater grotto and nightmarish castle painstakingly delivered with a painterly, handcrafted feel.  The beauty and underlying danger around every corner compliments the calm atmosphere of exploring this world. The music is another major highlight, with an orchestral score evoking the mystery and danger of Lemuria, as well as the build-up necessary to show Aurora’s coming of age. There are also some opera-esque pieces for dramatic combat sections, which really give an epic feeling to the boss battles and major fights. It’s one of the most memorable soundtracks for me in recent memory, with numerous tracks coming to mind even after finishing the game.The measure of a masterpiece does not come from a singular element. It is achieved through the seamless melding of every aspect of the creation into one, cohesive vision that artfully sends the message of the artists. Child of Light is a wonderful and beautiful game, uncompromising in it’s commitment to it’s writing choice. The visuals are gorgeous, with almost every screen could stand alone as a beautiful watercolor painting. The combat is deep and extremely enjoyable, the story an endearing one of a girl facing a new, threatening world. The exploration is ominous and foreboding, but inviting. Every aspect of Child of Light blends into this amazing, central whole, providing an incredibly memorable and personal experience that stands as one of the absolute best games of 2014. I hope this wonderful game eventually cements itself as a classic."
