76561198099942864,Recommended,256290,34491612,Posted: 25 August,all,iamtheinsanemegapinecone,"Gorgeous game, especially to play with kids age 6-10. Fairy tales and turn-based RPG fun, although the poetry is terrible, but then, when isn't it?"
76561198051874509,Recommended,256290,34537489,Posted: 27 August,all,greywolfe,"a sweet ""gateway"" rpg with a beautiful aesthetic.are you looking to get into rpg's, but all the rpg's terrify you because of their length and the ridiculous difficulty spike that goes along with managing stats, managing equipment, managing party members, doing the combat dance and generally worrying whether you're making all the right choices?if this is the case, i'd like to introduce you to child of light.  child of light is a very simple ""first"" rpg that you can finish in 10-12 hours [my playtime is excessive, because i play games slowly and i tend to try and find ALL THE THINGS.]how it all workschild of light's framework is that of a storybook.  the minute you start the game, it recounts a simple narrative that takes place in a fantasy world that feels exactly like those bedtime stories you used to hear as a child.  ""there was a princess"" ""she saw many strange things"" - i'm sure you know exactly what i mean.in this framework, you slowly collect party members that help you on your quest.  each party member has their own personality and their own strengths.  there are magic users, but each magic user does a different job.  there are physical characters, but each one tackles being physical in a different way.combat is turn based and largely stress free, but you can only ever have two party members on screen at any time during combat, where the enemy almost always has three [this is somewhat mitigated by the easy drop-in/drop-out nature of the fights:  when it's your turn, you can easily swap to one of your other party members.  you can also flee at the drop of a hat if it's your turn with no serious repurcussions.]there's no actual items to manage:  you get dust, which makes you better and jewels which you can forge into stat-boosting trinkets that do different things based on which equipment slot you put them into.  anything else you pick up is a part of the story.in the same vein, conversations are scripted.  you don't need to worry about getting things wrong in conversation trees, because everything that is said is ""the right thing at the right time to the right person.""with all this going for it, it's easy to make a case for this as your first rpg if you're even a little on the fence about the genre.  the visuals are charming, the music is beautiful [if repetitive - it's one of the very few downsides] and the story is sweet [though quite trope-y.  you'll spot many of the story beats coming a mile away.]if you've never tried a rpg, i can heartily recommend this one.pros at a glanceshort, turn-based rpg with minimal ""rpg headaches""beautiful visuals and simple, heartfelt storya great game for being introduced to rpg'sa neat protgaonist and party memberscons at a glancethe combat numbers can seem a little overwhelming [3 enemies, HUGE damage spikes]the music, while beautiful is repetitivethose rhyming couplets [it's a great conceit stretched WAY too thin.]terrifically meh dlc.  buy the dresses and golem pack.  ignore the rest."
