76561198002555011,Recommended,256290,13732467,"Posted: 30 December, 2014",all,MattyVanHalen,"Child of Light is a very artistic roleplaying adventure game that is unique in a lot of ways.  With impressive hand-drawn graphics in the background, unique looking characters and monsters, and excellent lighting, this game at first impression looks fantastic.  Throw in an interesting storyline written in poetic prose that makes dialogue feel fun and alive, a beautiful soundtrack, and flowing gameplay, and that makes Child of Light more than worth getting.As far as gameplay goes, you control Aurora, the main character--a female protagonist--and journey through the lands of Lemuria, running, jumping, and flying.  Along the way, you find interesting and unique NPCs that will join your party, and more importantly, a firefly named Igniculus, that becomes a major part of the player's mouse controls.  With Igniculus, you slow down monsters, pick up items out of reach, heal your characters, and perform many other functions in and out of combat.The combat system is very different, with a feel of turn-based roleplaying games with a time-delay system.  Timing attacks, usage of items, using Igniculus to slow down monsters, and swapping party members in and out, is all a vital part of succeeding in this somewhat difficult game.  Once fights are completed, you are rewarded with experience and items, where you can build each of your characters through certain skill paths.Child of Light isn't without its flaws, however.  The fact that you can only use two party members at a time, without exchanging during combat, leaves the player unable to use all of his or her characters.  I found myself throughout the entire game using mainly only Aurora (being the main character) and one other character, because he just simply felt better than the others.  On top of that, while the combat system is well-designed, it can lead to very time-consuming battles, where it feels like you simply get nowhere, as you are constantly pressured, overwhelmed, and interrupted, which moves characters back down the timeline to perform an attack.  Also, because of this, most items appear to be pretty worthless, because attacks are so important to deliver successfully and quickly; there simply isn't enough time to use most items in the game.All in all, Child of Light is a very beautiful, inspiring, well-crafted game with a lot of added humor and fun for all ages.  I can't rate this as high as other reviews because the downsides really killed the game for me after a while, but I do recommend this game nontheless.  I rate it a 7.3 out of 10."
