76561197970695064,Recommended,256290,10038042,"Posted: 6 May, 2014",all,Slimey,"OK, first off at first glance this isn't the kind of thign that would noramlly get me into it that much. I'm eclectic in tastes, but lately I've moved away from hack n slash RPG's and FPS's a little. Sure I have spent hours running around battlefields shooting terrorists etc. in COD et al, and delved into the depths of Dragon Age and Skyrim, but every now anf then I pull back and spend a bit of time on one of the Total War series, just to chnge the pace. SO when I was getting nostalgic the other week I thought I'd delve into the old adventure game genre, less real time, more puzzle solving etc.So I was having a browse through the Steam Store and came across this. At first glance I was, OK looks interesting, but is it too childish and simple for me? I mean I've played through Bookworm adventures and Peggle, so I'm not adverse to the 'toy' style games every now and then. But I wasn't sure about playing through something slow and reminiscent of the old text adventures. In the surface it does seem like that kind of game. But I had a look around the web and saw some good things written about CoL, so I thought, for £12 how bad can it get? In the end, I can always gift the game off to someone and I won't have dropped £30-40 on a bust.Well, no fear, because this is one of those few games I will likely return to some time from now and enjoy all over again. To use a single word to sum up a game, which can be very hard sometimes, this is majestic! Or maybe sumptuous is a better word? Or enthralling? Or….No, one word won’t do. The artistry involved, the story telling, the simple but challenging mechanics that just want to keep you playing another ½ hour when you should do something productive (or sleep). It all adds up to one of the best games I have ever played. It’s well paced without being too frantic (combat) or too laconic (travelling around the map).I can thoroughly recommend this to anyone except the spotty teen who simply has to have the biggest baddest gun, the highest score, or the most rad in game character. It’s a great game to relax with if you are in the mood for something less hectic.My only downer on this, if you can call it that, is its over too soon if you pursue the main quest, though you can play through once you’ve completed that and tick off the little side quests etc. I’d like to see some DLC to expand the experience (the map does actually hint at additional locations as yet unlocked). But for £12, who am I kidding. You could pay £20+ for this and be satisfied.Excellent adventure! 96% (if you have to put a rating on it)"
