,Not Recommended,256290,28696459,"Posted: 26 December, 2016",all,Z o,"The art style in this game is fantastic - the color choices and character designs are top notch.Regrettably, I have to say the game is poorly written. The overall story might be good, but I'll never know: the forced rhyme-speech of every character in this game (at least, the handful that I encountered in the prologue + first hour of play) is simply unbearable.  That is to say, every character in this game speaks in rhymes (not riddles or anything, just rhymes).  It would be slightly amusing if executed well, but unfortunately the dialogue between characters is butchered to an unreal degree all for the sake of the pointless rhyming.  Seriously, the ""poet"" behind this game should stick to handing in assignments to his or her third grade teacher.But if you don't care about characters breaking versimilitude by occasionally slipping into Yoda-sentence-structure to piece together yet another forced rhyme with a thesaurus-sourced vocab choice, you might like this game.One thing that you might want to know before buying this game (I didn't realize it) is that combat isn't executed in the manner traditional to side scrollers: unlike Trine, Dust, or Bastion, combat in this game plays out like a JRPG.  Like in Chrono Trigger you can approach an enemy, then the game will cut-scene into a small arena where you play the battle out in a turn-based manner.This isn't necessarily a detractor from the game if you enjoy that kind of combat, but I have to admit I was a little disappointed since I happen to prefer side scrolling battle (jumping around, aiming, choosing correct weapons, etc.) over the JRPG style (conserving your mana until you need it, spending a turn to use a potion when necessary, etc.).I hope you found this review useful."
