,Not Recommended,256290,34106592,Posted: 8 August,all,Mr. Matt,"I find that there's a fine line to walk when it comes to a setting and story being airy and whimsical. Child of Light's dialog/story are presented as poetry, and it came off to me as very dismissive of anything being all that important. The game doesn't appear to be made for small children, but the dialog sounds to me like a bedtime story an adult would read to a small child in a soft tone, completely devoid of substance or sincerity; just trying to get the little rugrat to fall asleep rather than to actually entertain.The music is charming, and the art style is rather pretty, which I feel are the game's biggest positives. The combat is alright, though it's clearly at a level of difficulty higher than what a small child could handle, so this further evidences that the story was meant for more mature people capable of winning its battles.Unfortunately, the whimsy of its story completely obliterated all sense of urgency or interest I had in the game. With the gameplay not being terribly entertaining for me, despite the fact that I like turn-based RPG combat just fine, I needed characters and story that would keep me interested and wanting to go on. I certainly don't demand really mature themes or grittiness or anything of that sort, and find some whimsy fun. However, everything feltsoinconsequential and airy to me in Child of Light that I could not feel even the least bit compelled to continue, despite paying for it at launch and sinking 10+ hours into it. I honestly don't know how I got the will to play that long."
