,Not Recommended,256290,31536813,Posted: 3 May,all,Tannhäuser,"At it's core, I really love Child of Light. The gameplay is interesting, everything is very pretty and aesthetically pleasing, and the story is fairly well done. However, a few awful missteps made me immediately drop the game with zero motivation to ever finish it.My major issue with the game is a spoiler, so if you wish to play through the game unspoiled, I will just say this: Story is important, but not when you absolutely punish and cripple the player for no reason if they make certain choices.Here is my complaint put more specifically:Some time into the game you gain access to the protagonist's sister, Norah. She is my absolute favorite character in the game, and I quickly made her the 'Leader' of my team, running her in every battle and pouring all of my resources into making her as strong as possible.It occurred to me that there might be a mod or some setting that allowed you to change your in-game character to one of your party members, so I did a quick google search to see if it that was possible. What I discovered is that further into the game, Norah betrays your party, becoming unplayable for the rest of the game. While this was not only very disappointing from a story perspective, as I really liked her character, it wascompletely unacceptablefrom a gameplay standpoint. I had poured almost all of my resources into her first, running her in every battle, making her the strongest (and highest leveled) member of my team and only using the leftovers on the others. I was playing on the highest difficulty, and I was doing extremely well. When she leaves your team? You loseeverythingyou put into her. There is no compensation. No way to get her or your resources back. Just ""Woops, guess you shouldn't have leveled/geared that character huh?""At that point I dropped the game. In my mind that was an incredibly stupid move on the developer's part, to suprise you by removing one of your characters with no warning, causing you to lose all of the resources spent on them. I doubt I would've been able to complete the game with the rest of my team as they were. You may say ""You shouldn't put all your eggs in one basket"", but there was no reason for me to believe that the player would be subject to such an underhanded move, and nor should there have been. It's just bad game design."
,Not Recommended,256290,12116056,"Posted: 16 September, 2014",all,nutcrackr,"Child of Light is a basic 2D adventure through the fantasy land of Lemuria. The princess, Aurora, has died and her papa has lost hope, but with the help of unusual friends there is no time to mope. Aurora battles darkness with friends anew, hoping to see this spiritual adventure through. Magicians, jesters and warriors unite to give the princess one last chance. With each battle won, Aurora makes her advance.The attractive world of Lemura is rendered with Ubi-Art Framework, but the lack of noteworthy gameplay starts to hurt. Aurora walks or flies across colorful landscapes, stumbling upon treasures and wishes.  Wishes ignite your friendly orb of light and treasures prevent you sleeping with the fishes. The orb stuns foes left and right, but minimal exploration makes the adventure slight.As you collide with foes, you are thrust into a contrived battle pose. Battles have your friends taking turns to eliminate foes counting three. But the nature of the combat propels enjoyment far out to sea. You jostle to deal elemental damage to susceptible foes, yet constant interrupts keep you on your toes. Once you become a master tactician, bosses turn interrupts into a war of attrition. Some bosses succumb after half an hour, making boss battles repetitive and sour. Combat is tolerable at best - how much you can endure is the true test.Just as the world lacks excitement, the un-voiced dialogue becomes an indictment. Exactly as this review is written before you, the authors were smitten with rhyming too. Some might think it funny or clever, but it becomes like persistent bad weather. If instead you find this readable, then you’ll likely find the narrative tolerable. Know that there is little that proves enlightening, even as you battle forces most frightening.If Lemuria is the land we are sent to after death, try to avoid the reaper long after your last breath. If you insist on buying Child of Light to get your arty platforming hit, don’t complain when you discover it’s quite sh…"
