,Recommended,256290,10994417,"Posted: 1 July, 2014",all,Silvera Sea,"What can I say about the game that hasn’t been said already?From the start Child of Light reveals itself to be more than your average platformer. A cutscene opens up the game, like most other games use to converse, but the difference is tantalizing, delightful, rhyming in verse. It flowed like a lullaby, written as a bedtime story.I eagerly played when I had the time to, not questioning the other games I had left behind to finish this one. The artwork and music immediately drew me in each time I opened the game, and the story equally as enticing, even just for its simplicity. Over the time I played it I grew to love it for its beauty and mastery, its charm, and its whimsy.I cannot express how much joy I found in playing this game. This is video gaming at its finest, where all forms of art are mastered beautifully. The soundtrack, melancholic yet hopeful, weaves with the water colored imagery and story, and even the turn based combat was invigorating. If you are a connoisseur of art, this is a game you would not want to miss.The entire piece is rich; each singular medium flavorful in its execution. Some may call the story childish, however I believe its simplicity is one of its most emotionally impactful factors. You don’t need to second guess your mind, for your eyes, your ears, and your heart will write the story for you.This is the game I would use to introduce others to games, to show them just how far gaming can go. I bought it expecting a game, and left with an experience.“Close your eyes, let goAnd drift off to sleep.”"
