,Recommended,256290,16043014,"Posted: 28 May, 2015",all,FanarnarBoi,"Warning: Long reviewIntroductionLet's get straight to the point: Child of Light is one of the most charming, adorable, beautiful, entrancing, engaging game I've played in the recent past. Its simplistic story, its charismatic cast of characters, its alluring art style, and its serene, soothing soundtrack all captivated me to the very end, and then some. I still hum Aurora's Theme and Off to Sleep to this day. If you have $15 to spare, you can't go wrong with Child of Light.It was developed by the creative minds at Ubisoft Montreal (don't cringe). One employee had the idea for a Free-to-Play Final Fantasy. He presented the idea to his higher-ups, and they agreed to fund it and give it resources. After much development, it was released in April 2014 for PC, PS3, and Xbox 360. It was later ported to Wii U, PS4, Xbox One, and Vita, and it even got a physical retail release on the Vita, the only physical release for the game. There are numerous DLC packs for Child of Light, none of which are essential or necessary. There is one called the Golem Pack, which adds a new quest and party member, and two costume DLCs for Aurora. The rest are oculi bundles, which are small stat boosting items. You could breeze through the game without DLC, so don't worry about it being pay-to-win.Story and SettingThe journey starts with the duke of Austria's only daughter, Aurora, passing away of an illness. But then she wakes up in a fantastical world called Lemuria. Anthropomorphized animals, dwarves, giants, and magic inhabit this mystical land, but there are also plenty of foes that stand in Aurora's way. If you're arachnophobic, I recommend playing this game with someone else. Within the first couple of chapters, Aurora befriends a talking firefly, picks up a sword, and starts vanquishing any dark creatures that cross her path. Throughout the game, she meets quite the colourful ensemble of characters, including a brother-sister jester duo, a rat (the literal one), and a dwarf proficient in magic. The premise of the story is that a dark queen has stolen the sun, the stars and the moon (don't ask how), and Aurora must return them to restore peace and light to Lemuria. There is laughter, there is sadness, there is friendship, there is betrayal. It's not the most complex or intricate of narratives, but it serves its purpose.Gameplay and PresentationThe gameplay of Child of Light consists of exploring a 2D overworld, and battling dark creatures in a turn-based JRPG style system. The battle system is quite reminiscent of Final Fantasy VII (Active Time Battle). There is a bar at the bottom of the screen that is split into two sections: ""Wait"" time and ""Cast"" time. Once a character reaches the cast bar, the player can choose an action: ""Act"", ""Party"", ""Potions"", or ""Flee"". The latter three are self explanatory. Choosing Act displays attacks or spells your character can perform, how much magic it takes to perform it, and how much time it takes to perform it. Length can range from Instant to Very Long, depending on how powerful the attack or spell is. Timing is very important in Child of Light. If either the enemy or the player successfully lands a hit on the other while they are in the cast zone, they are interrupted, sending them back on the timeline. This is crucial to winning battles, and slowing the enemy and quickening your party helps immensely. Once you finish a battle, experience points are awarded. Leveling up a character grants skill points, which can be spent on each individual character's skill tree to acquire more spells and perks. All party members get the same amount of experience, regardless if they fought in a battle or not.Outside of battles, Aurora can explore the overworld and talk to various people. Some of these people have quests to give you. These are optional side quests that have no impact on the main story. There are side dungeons with enemies and loot scattered around Lemuria. Loot consists of either potions are oculi, which are special gems used for stat boosting and other benefits. Aurora's firefly friend, Igniculus, can provide light in dark spaces, open hidden chests, solve puzzles, and slow enemies in battle. Child of Light can be played with two players, with one person controlling Aurora and one person controlling Igniculus.The soundtrack of the game was composed by a famous French Canadian singer known as Coeur de Pirate. It's comprised of orchestral themes and 1 song at the end. You can buy the soundtrack on her bandcamp site, or get it at a retailer for $15. The soundtrack not only adds atmosphere and mood to the game, but synthesizes really well with the watercolour art, making the entire presentation seem fairytale-like. Combine that with the rhyming and you're basically playing an extremely well assembled children's book. Speaking of the art, it was hand-painted and then rendered into the UbiArt Framework engine (same engine as Rayman Legends). The art has a calming effect and is entrancing when exploring.Now we arrive at the most divisive component of Child of Light: the rhyming. Some people adore it and find it charming, others depise it and find it annoying and repetitive. Instead of spoken dialogue, characters speak through text. The writers made an effort to make almost every line in the game rhyme with another. In my opinion, I admire this method of exposition, and I find it cute. Some might disagree, and that's completely fine. Just keep in mind that if you are considering playing this, you will be reading quite a bit of poetry. I advise you to watch a bit of gameplay and see if the rhyming appeals to you, because it's a large component of Child of Light. Some of it is flawlessly delivered, other times it's kind of rough, which is understandable. My favourite lines occur in Chapter 6, spoken by Aurora and Igniculus:""Aurora, what is love known by?""""When it hurts to say goodbye.""Complaints and ConclusionNo game is perfect. It's unfortunate, but I have to acknowledge some complaints I had while playing. You may not agree with these points, and that's fine. Just my opinion.1. The final segments of the last chapters felt a little rushed. You beat a boss, you watch a cutscene, then you're thrust straight into the final boss. Personally, I would have prefered one final dungeon or at least the ability to customize my oculi before fighting.2. Uplay. Personally, I have had no problems with it, other than a small cloud saving issue. One of my friends bought the game but he couldn't play it. While he met the minimum requirements listed on the Steam page, Uplay said that his CPU did not. I have heard many other horror stories about Ubisoft's infamous DRM client, so be wary.Despite the above, I thoroughly enjoyed Child of Light. It runs well, it looks amazing, it sounds beautiful, some moments in the story are surprisingly emotional, the characters are likable, the writing is witty, and the gameplay is easy to learn and is a great starter to the turn based genre of games. It's an experience like no other. If you have $15 to spend, spend it on this. You will not regret it. As a bonus, here's a small piece I wrote when I finished the game.Sixteen hours have come and gone,The end was void of dance, but not song.The princess now graduates to queen,Ruling the world of many colours, purple through green.It was an experience like no other.I can't imagine having another.But now it vanishes from my ever-growing list,One I shall beat with an iron fist."
