76561198008152844,Not Recommended,256290,18897441,"Posted: 5 November, 2015",all,Aleachjed,"The look of the game is pretty and unique, but you get accustomed to it quickly and it fails to keep suprising you. The rhyming of every voiceover and dialogue is intereresting in the beginning, but you quickly grow tired of it. Its still fun exploring the well-crafted world and interacting with the childish, but fun characters. The controls feel a bit rough compared to real plattformers (like Ori and the Blind Forest), but it's fun and relaxing once you can fly around.I stopped playing early because I realy don't like the combat system. The combination of plattformer and turn-based-combat doesn't work for me, it always roughs up my flow when the fighting starts. True, you can avoid most fights, but fighting is the only way to level up, and there are fights you HAVE to take, so you need the XP to stay competitive.I'm not that enthusiastic about classic RPG combat without positioning anyway. But there are games who manage to still make it fun. This game doesn't. Even with a few minor innovations, its brutally repetitive after a few fights. The skill trees are strange and don't give you the feeling of realy being able to develop a character in the direction of your chosing. And no ability you ever use in a fight makes you feel the least bit awesome.The game sure has it's qualities, particularly in the art department. There are so many background layers, and sometimes super interesting things are happening there, with giant creatures moving around in the distance (I realy cheered for that when I noticed it). The animations are super smooth, i just kept turning for while just to whirl the characters hair around her face.But at the end, the gameplay does not deliver. Its neither a good platformer (not the smoothest controls, no real skill challenges), nor a good RPG (boring skilltrees, generic combats). The look and the few innovations can't sell it."
