76561198054284980,Recommended,256290,16547221,"Posted: 20 June, 2015",all,Jaeger Bomb,"Child of Light is a hybrid of side-scrolling adventure and turn-based action (i.e like Final Fantasy VII). It is a charming game that instantly pulled me in with its beautiful artwork-styled graphics and emotional, heartfelt sound track.Story: Child of Light starts with a young girl named Aurora who is from 1895 Austria. One day, she disappears from her loving father's grasp and is transported to a dream-like world known as Lemuria. As you progress through the game, many events unfold regarding Aurora's father the Duke and you will see why Aurora is part of this new and strange world. The story is beautifully tragic, told with rhymes that work well for the most part and the ending is fairly sad.Graphics: The graphics of this game just pop off the screen. Rarely, have I been blown away and completely immersed by a game's visuals that are as breathtaking as Child of Light's which looks like it leaped off the canvas of an artist! The way the game is presented works will to complement the game's fairytale story.Gameplay: It bends the traditional conventions of an RPG by mixing side-scrolling adventure and turn-based action. Even though it may be strange to many fans of games such as Final Fantasy at first, you will come to get used to the mechanics and I believe that you will enjoy it much more. Battles happen when Aurora touches a creature and this is when the game switches to turn-based. I like that Child of Light takes inspiration from newer RPGs in that it is more action-packed with the interrupt mechanic (where spells or action of someone can be halted if they are hit first) and that Igniculus, the firefly plays a major role during combat. You can use the left-trigger on consoles to lighten up the firefly which causes enemies to be slowed OR to heal allies in a fight. It is an innovative system that is a lot of fun and keeps you on your toes.Overall, Child of Light is one of my favourite RPGs (along with Final Fantasy VII and IX) and all the elements mesh together well to create a unique experience that is very memorable.I'd give the game a 9/10."
