76561198056620099,Recommended,256290,20426642,"Posted: 9 January, 2016",all,Captain Cummerbund,"If you've looked at the videos/screenshots above, then you're already familiar with the game's strongest selling point - it's graphics, and the atmosphere it crafts. Some other thoughts on the game:+/- Challenging, but not difficult.+ Engaging battles - it is turn based, but at the same time you have to make lots of decisions in real time. In essence, you need to be quite active while ""waiting"" for your turn: the game implements an interrupt mechanism, as well as control on how to pace the battle, and trade offs on whether or not to impose this control. Very fun.+ Nice versatility when it comes to customizing your character build on level up.+ The game is relatively quick and has a nice pacing to it. At no point does it feel bogged down in grinding, or pointless side quests.- The game advertises that you can hook up a second controller, but the range of things that a buddy can do is  very limited and very heavy on support. I doubt this is much fun.- ""Puzzles"" are solvable by grade schoolers. When will they make a game that doesn't take for granted the intelligence of their audience??+/- The mythology is deliberately and poetically vague. Some people find this frustrating, but I find it refreshing to not have everything spelled out.+/- Finally, this is about the most melancholic coming-of-age RPG there is. At one point you meet a jester named Tristus with tears streaming down its face, for goodness sake.9/10, and absolutely worth the price anytime you can get this game during a Steam sale."
