,Recommended,256290,13903078,"Posted: 8 January, 2015",all,Takalol,"A masterpiece of art, but just a average game as it is. This game draws from JRPGs such as Chrono Trigger and Grandia (or Grandia 2?), feels very Zeldaesque on some parts, looks a bit like Aquaria on other ones, and has western fairytales as a model on how the story unfolds.This game has an epic Pan's Labyrinth feeling to it, looking like a dark fairytale as its story unfolds with magnificent visuals and a fitting soundtrack.The story has a nice sense of progression, you feel the progress and feel rewarded as you play through the game.It feels unique, the game seems handpainted all over it, including the 3D models, the movement and animations are perfect, you feel the innocence and the fragility of the character on the first instants of the game, you feel the weight of the sword on her hands and you feel like some dark places are really creepy and ominous.The soundtrack that accompanies the game is pretty well executed, it's not the best around, but its still fitting through the entire game and adds to the fairytale feeling of the whole experience.While the whole game feels astonishingly beautiful, what really inspired me to review it were the dialogues, all of them were written in prose, the whole narrative is driven by rhymes and poems sang by the characters while they venture Lemuria. Some simple lines are written so well that you'll be recalling them for days, and still feel glad to have experienced this game.This game as a work of arts, visuals, sounds and story are 10/10. A masterpiece.Now onto the ""game"" part of it, the mechanics are simple tight about JRPG that everyone knows well, feels a bit like the old Grandia 2 from PSX with a hint of Chrono Trigger on how you engage into fights, for the whole game you'll be going through simple Trine/Zelda puzzles while fighting (or not) mobs of the darkness, character customization comes from gems that you get while fighting mobs or finding treasures and through a simple skill system that looks a lot like Far Cry 3's. Too bad that some skills are almost mandatory for you to play through some parts of the game when playing on Hard, and that makes grinding a bit of a must if you chose the wrong skills early on. Fighting are simple enough to easily grasp onto them, but complex enough  so that if you want to play it well, you need to master every tiny bit of the fighting mechanics. The game is pretty linear as a whole, you don't get much to do on the side of the main story, and while all of the monsters are avoidable, fighting them is almost always a win-win on the grinding part, you level easily and fastly so that the whole grinding thing is less of a burden. As a game, without counting the masterfully done art, I'd rate it 7/10... It's just that nothing is really okay at all, but it's not bad, just feels flawed at times.Final Verdict : Play it. It's really good."
,Recommended,256290,13889508,"Posted: 7 January, 2015",all,Afinn,I can't say anything bad about this game. The art is beautiful and the gameplay is good and you don't need a powerful computer to run it. I highly recommend this game for people who want something just to play around with when you're feeling a bit lazy : 3
76561198084657727,Recommended,256290,13922456,"Posted: 10 January, 2015",all,Celtic Steel,"Before I begin this review proper, let me just say that tears and emo songs about Uplay are complete gash.  Uplay installs itself, you change the settings to always offline, and you never have to worry about it again.  All it means is you have one more click on one more menu than most steam games.  I understand you may not want Uplay, but lets not go overboard with the thing.I've only been playing for about an hour or so, but I am already in love with this game.  Child of Light is a very special game, one which provides a different experience from almost any RPG I have played.  It is similar to the Valkyrie Profile games in that it combines 2d platforming and turn-based JRPG style battles.  On the surface, its a simple game with simple but fun puzzles and simple but fun combat.However, at heart, this is a fabulous, storybook style experience with some amazing fairytale style artwork, gorgeous presentation and some of the best sound I've heard from a game in a long time.  The visiuals really stunned me as I guided Aurora through a hand-painted magical land, and the creative use of melancholic music reawakened the inner child in me.  The sound effects, from the pitter patter of Aurora's feet to the roars of monnsters and ghouls really brings the story to life.  And, to top it off, the dialogue is all presented in rthyme!Like I said, it is a simple but enjoyable game on the surface, but at heart it's a gripping fairytale adventure. Child of Light is more about experiencing the world and the story than the game play mechanics (which are fine, it must be said).  I don't really feel like I'm gaming when I boot this up; I feel more like I'm reading Wind in the Willows or something.  Overall, I'm having a blast playing this, and expect to enjoy it until its end."
