76561198081675887,Recommended,256290,13859931,"Posted: 5 January, 2015",all,Castawaye,"Child of Light comes off as a very, ""strange"" game at first. Once we enter the world of Lemuria, we are burdened with the task of finding the Stars, Moon, and Sun. We must traverse to the highest of the high and the lowest of the low, and some may ask, why? And just like any good old children's fairytale, we must do it in order to smite that which is evil, to see to it that justice will prevail. To smite the plague that is looming over Lemuria. And some of you at this point may ask, who are we? In our past lives we were a princess, a daughter of a king long past his time. And in our past lives, we were precarious and just like any loving daughter, we clung to our mother. So why is it that we must traverse the dangerous soils of Lemuria? To reclaim that which has been stolen? To prove to our predecessors that we can prevail the dark? Or is it because we are doing this solely for the sake of our own desires? To see our beloved father once again? As we traverse the lands of Lemuria, we are burdened with these questions, or at least some of you may be.  And, it's a good thing to ask these questions. To some, this may be a simple story of morality, a simple choice of good and evil, but one has to stop and ask; why are we doing all of this?So, as you have guessed, that was my way of handing down the story from one person to another. In a way, a game like Child Of Light, is very much story based as it is combat based, so of course having a good story is very welcome.  Some may find it bland, but others, like myself, may find its simplicity perfect.  And it really is. The way I put it may have sugar coated some parts, and may have extended on some other meanings, but to boil it down, it really is just like a fairytale. It's something mystical and Child of Light is just that. A journey filled with mysticism.Like I said, Child of Light is one part story, but also one part combat. The combat system is something akin to old style RPG's, in which, once your turn queue is up, you will be able to go through a number of options such as attacking, defending, or using an item.  But, Child of Light gives it a little twist. The combat system revolves mainly around a small time gauge at the bottom of your screen. Characters will have to move to the end of the gauge before they can initiate any moves. But if they are interpreted by enemies that are faster than them, then they will be kicked back on the gauge, and have their move cancelled. This mechanic can also work against enemies, effectively creating a way for players to strategically plan out their moves so that they can interrupt their enemies and keep up an onslaught of moves. Later on, things get more complicated as interrupting may actually work against you due to enemies possessing counter abilities , but that's for later in the game. To summarize, the core of the combat is pretty much a gauge based RPG.With both of these elements converging and creating a package known as Child of Light, one may ask, haven't I forgotten a key aspect? And I have, and that is, music. The music at times, helped create a sense of tension, sadness, and excitement. In battle and story wise, each musical piece that was played was played in conjunction to what was happening on screen. Every piece helped add on to the mood, and every piece was very well made. In times of despair, all we really need, is for a calm and soothing tune to settle our dread. And with every triumph, there must have been an epic to follow. Child of Light brings these elements and many more to life with its well crafted music.Over all, Child of Light is a well made game, and despite it not being perfect or majorly impressing me, I still had a ton of fun travelling Lemuria along with the companions that decided to join me."
