,Recommended,256290,10227824,"Posted: 25 May, 2014",all,Eth3real,"My breakdown of why you should/shouldn't get Child of Light:+ the beautiful water colour landscapes and characters which gives the impression of watching a painting unfold+the characters who join you on your adventures (all of whom are decidedly unconventional and unique)+ the soundtrack, which is possibly THE standout element of the entire game (yes the art style is gorgeous but the music is absolutely flawless)+ the complex character advancement, which includes allocating points into a skill tree with several branches making it tough to decide where to commit your points+ and - the battle system, which may or may not be to everyone's liking, it is a combination of turn based and real time in that both sides move on an action bar and can be interrupted or knocked back with the right strategy- as previously stated, there are elements of combat which can be quite frustrating: sometimes you'll do a lot of damage to enemies with phsyical AND magical attacks, other times you'll do almost no damage with either, and it can often be almost impossible to know what particular type of attack an enemy is weak against which makes for some frustrating battles- the lack of voice acting. there is a little but it's pretty much just in the form of narration-the coop element isn't the best and while one person is able to control Igniculus it doesn't really give that person much to do besides take a back seat and play more of a supporting role"
