76561198104647655,Recommended,256290,11090600,"Posted: 5 July, 2014",all,pieandpi,"Pros:Beautiful art, both visual and written.The backgrounds and character designs showed a high level of attention to detail and supported the thematic content. There was one glitch I noticed where the main character briefly loses her hair (!!). I don't usually like poetry with repetitive hard rhymes, but in this case, the rhyming dialogue built up the fairytale aesthetic.Diverse cast of characters.Four (of nine) of the playable characters are female, and the three main villains are also women.The story features diverse female relationships not revolving around men (and definitely passes the Bechdel test). My only caveat is that that all characters were either light-skinned or nonhuman.Coming-of-age themes.The themes are well-supported by the story, artistic choices, character arcs, and even some of the game mechanics.Game mechanics.The battle system is an easy-to-learn RPG style that enables reasonably good game pacing (little actual grinding is required to get through normal difficulty). There's a little bit of platforming and a little bit of puzzling, but it never becomes frustrating.Cons:Story.The ending is rushed,as you proceed into the final battle directly after defeating the second of three main villains. There's a lot of build-upwith the confessionsthat for me never really paid off. I have heard that a sequel is planned, which makes some of the lack of resolution make sense, but there were too many questions left unanswered, and at that point, I was invested enough that the ending was disappointing.Verdict:Give Ubisoft your money. This game is too pretty not to play. Especially for gaming novices, it's a great introduction to several core gaming types."
