,Recommended,256290,12667175,"Posted: 28 October, 2014",all,CerebralCort-X,"I absolutely adored the artstyle used in this game. Watercolor? Yes, please. The music was beautiful albeit a bit sad, but I think it's cool that it plays a part in the story. The way the story was narrated was rather enchanting. Although there were a bunch of cliches, especially with the choice of antagonists, the story had a number of twists of its own that made it different from the rest.This game is like a storybook brought to life wherein you control the main protagonist who, by the way, is a charming little spitfire of a princess who carries a sword that's obviously too big and heavy for her size. I love it when she struggles with her weapon after every fight. I'm not really fond of turnbased fighting, but this one was manageable. The protagonist and her band of equally talented misfits had their own list of backstories and interesting skills that made each of them important in their own right.Although the game is quite short, the whole package (story, artwork, music, etc.) that comes with it makes up for this shortcoming. I grabbed this game when it was on sale, but had I known that it was going to be such a fun experience for me, I would have gotten this game at its full price without thinking twice.If you're the type to find it hard to let go of a game after finishing it, then this one's for you. You still have to stay for a bit to finish some sidequests which, just in case you wanted to know, require a lot of patience and a keen eye since you would have to do a lot of exploring to find clues and hidden places you might have missed before. This isn't a problem for a wee princess with fairy wings though.I'm giving this game a 9 out of 10."
