,Recommended,256290,12489168,"Posted: 14 October, 2014",all,Evly,"Child of Light follows the story of Aurora, a princess who has fallen into a deep sleep and awakes in the mythical land of Lemuria. Along the way Aurora meets strange friends who help her fight through the monsters of Lemuria in order to save her father from death. The game takes on many aspects of well known fairy tales such as Sleeping Beauty and is written entirely in iambic pentameter.The Pros:Combat - Combat is done in a jrpg style. It is indepth as well as entertaining. How combat centered the game will be is determined by your difficulty level. If you're the type of person who only wants a casual experiance and a story, great, you can breeze through the combat on easy. For those of you who enjoy a challenge, bump up the difficulty.Art - If you take one look at the beautiful watercolors of Lemuria, you will see why so many people are drawn to this game. From dark forests to high cliffs and to under water palaces, the artsits behind Child of Light never fail to deliver a stunning, graceful, and beautiful scene.The Cons:Characters - All though it's obvious that Ubisoft Montreal wanted to make the game feel like a classic fairy tale, they may have succeeded all too well. The characters, though unique in their own way, vary little from their classic archetypes. Overall this has damaged the game for many people.Overall, I would say buy the game. If you're overly concerned about the flat characters, buy the game when it's on sale. The experiance was enjoyable enough to play through it at least once, although I suspect that eventually I will play through the game again."
76561198076368962,Recommended,256290,10894674,"Posted: 27 June, 2014",all,Bees,"Since I saw the trailer a few months before release, I've been looking forward to playing this game.  Seeing a game starring a little girl on an epic hero quest is something I don't see very frequently, and my interest was piqued right away. While by no means a perfect game, I'd say it lived up fairly well to my expectations.This game's greatest strength I would say is the aesthetics. The environment, monsters, and characters (excepting Aurora, the Queen, and the Queen's daughters) are 2D drawings. The environments especially are gorgeous, evoking a storybook feeling. For some, the rhyming might be a bit off-putting, but to be honest it's only distracting if you're consciously trying to figure out the rhyming system as you read. At first, I was trying to figure out if they were going for couplets, or ABAB alternating rhyme, or limericks, or if certain characters used different rhyme styles. (On a side note, I found it amusingly meta that the other characters correct Rubella because she doesn't complete her rhymes when speaking.) The soundtrack is beautiful as well.I've heard that people complained about the gameplay - while I wouldn't imagine it would satisfy people wanting to get really hardcore into the game, I found it entertaining enough. It's simplistic and fairly easy, a scrolling platformer combined with RPG style battles. For me, the fact that you can fly more than makes up for it.My only big complaint is that the game was too short. I'm all for short games, even if they are RPGS but it was paced in such a way that the time between rising action => climax => resolution seemed too short and a little rushed. The fact that there isn't an opportunity to change your oculi after your battle with Nox before you get cutscened into the final boss fight with Umbra had me floundering for a bit. I suspect the developers were running out of funds or time. I think that is also the cause for the lack of character development for Nox and especially Cordelia. I would have liked to see more about their motivations. However, the fact that it's an indie game makes more forgiving of that kind of thing.All in all, I would say that this is a game that is definitely worth playing, despite its length/pacing and minor characterization issues. It has a beautiful design and soundtrack, it's fun to play, and it's wonderful to see a little girl as protagonist in the role of savior hero. If the confessions in the game are anything to go by, the developers were thinking of doing a sequel having to do with a woman from the modern era stuck in Lemuria, and I'd be looking forward to seeing."
