,Recommended,256290,13398725,"Posted: 15 December, 2014",all,Swampernova,"Ubisoft hasn't had a good 2014, Watch Dogs didn't live up to it's hype even though I still enjoyed it for what it was, Assassin's Creed Unity became a buggy mess at launch and was considered dissapointing compared to previous games, Assassin's Creed Rogue is just DLC packaged into a full-game and The Crew also isn't looking too good, don't know about Far Cry 4 though. I hope that in time those two games (Unity and The Crew) get better through patching and updating.However, Ubisoft Montreal did manage to create one of the best RPG's this year, which is Child of Light and I enjoyed every moment of it.Child of LIght takes place in 1895 Austria where the Duke's daughter Aurora, wakes up in an unfamiliar land called Lemuria. On a ardous quest to return home, she starts encountering monster's who serve Umbra, who is responsible for the land's turmoil and for stealing the moon, the sun and the stars which are the embodiements of light, Umbra is the opposite of Light (Good) which is Dark (Evil). To aid Aurora in her journey, she meets several unique companions and begin's jolly cooperation with them, killing monsters for loot and recieving xp together, and completing side-quests for personal gain and to help Lemuria's townsfolk.Gameplay: The game starts out as a 2d platformer which is pretty solid in terms of movement and animations. In combat mode, it's reminescent to JRPG games with it's action turn based system. one of the game's mechanics is that down the bottom center of the screen you have a meter which sways to the right till it reaches the casting phase, at this point enemies can actually stop you by reaching the end of the meter but you can as well by using Igniculus, your firefly companion to slow them down.before the end of that meter, you get time to make your decision whether you want to initiate an attack, use a potion, retreat from battle or switch party members, your standard options basically. Combat in this game is fun and I usually prefer action-based combat like Dark Souls. The bosses are pretty epic as well.Story: It's like a story with two sides of the coin, one side is different from one another but they are at conflict. They cannot co-exist with one another and the main character Aurora, is dragged into all of this. Light and Dark and their place in the world start to unfold throughout Aurora's adventure. she is compassionate and friendly towards the people she helps, towards her fellow companions, her friends and her family. But she is also struggling to understand her situation and why this had happened to her. The other characters are also great and stand out, they have their personalities and indifferences, my favourites were Rubella and Finn. In terms of dialogue it's different to other game's I've played. Every piece of dialogue given by the characters in Child of Light including the Narrator, is told in a poetic manner and it's great and it works and It wasn't what I was expecting.Music: When exploring the world of Lemuria it's peaceful, and harmonic and the memorable piece played with the flute that Aurora uses has a powerful, cheerful effect to the nearby people, especially in their times of strife and despair. When combat ensues it changes it's musical style and becomes epic, and empowering. It's one of my favourite aspects of Boss battles and the game's composer Couer de pirate does a fantastic job at capturing those feelings.Graphics: It looks visually appealing, mainly through it's artstyle, the artstyle itself carries the game's atmosphere and tone. Lemuria is somewhat of a ruined land, corrupted by the evil queen Umbra, whatever beauty remains in the land, gradually becomes more and more barren and bleak. as Umbra continues to spread her seeds. The locations are varied too, Deep Forests, Coastal wastelands, Volcanic Tunnels, Abandoned Castles, A city on top of a giant humanoid mountain, A dark sunless fortress and Crystal lairs.Overall: Child of Light is a special treat, it's one of Ubisoft's best titles to date and also one of the best RPG's in recent memory. a memorable experience with great characters, fun combat, great soundtrack and beautiful artwork. Don't let the name Ubisoft fool you into thinking it's a buggy, half♥♥♥♥♥♥♥game because I'm telling you right now, it isn't."
