76561198058851558,Recommended,256290,13979054,"Posted: 13 January, 2015",all,k00p,"Child of Light is a casual platformer with combat vaguely reminiscent of some Final Fantasies; uniquely and creatively simple and engaging. It is not a difficult game by nature, though the more challenging of the game’s difficulty levels does compel one to spend at least some time thinking about their tactics and fighting enemies they could otherwise bypass to gain levels (not a bad thing at all, imo). I found myself impressed with the effectiveness of the design; it satisfies every basic expectation I'd have of any RPG.That said, the relaxing gameplay is simply a vessel for the game’s beautiful imagery, atmosphere, and story. The protagonist is a young girl named Aurora from Austria who awakens in a fantasy world, Lemuria, where she must restore hope for its denizens by reclaiming the moon and stars from the night. An array of eccentric companions join her on the quest, each possessing their own unique personality and abilities which become invaluable as she battles wolves, gargoyles, wraiths, giants, and other fiends. The entirety of the story is told in dialogue, and the entirety of the dialogue is told in loose rhyme, creating a very pure form of fairy tale to experience.Child of Light offers not only a lovely story and world to explore and save, but tops it all off with an outstanding soundtrack that echoes Lemuria’s own beauty and conflict. I’ve spent countless hours listening to it even while not playing; if you value music at all, it is easily Child of Light’s best quality and I strongly recommend looking some of it up online if you're curious.It can be noted that in order to play Child of Light, you will need to download Uplay and create an account. Most of the negative comments regarding CoL seem to revolve around this minor inconvenience, but I didn’t find it to be a considerable bother in the least. If you’re unfamiliar, Uplay simply runs in the background and can be likened to Steam, Origin, or similar programs. It takes minutes to download, puts no measurable load on the CPU, and can be literally forgotten about thereafter.*   *   *   *   *Child of Light is a fantastic game with enjoyable gameplay, quaint characters, fascinating atmosphere, charming story, and beautiful music."
