76561198153594939,Recommended,256290,13279565,"Posted: 7 December, 2014",all,xelhes05,"First and most importantly, the game is absolutely amazing to look at. The visuals, along with the soundtrack, are what make the game so enjoyable for me and the main reason I have replayed it a few times. The art style reminds me of a pop-up book with a hand drawn feel to it, all the characters minus Aurora and a few others (who are 3D models) matching this 2D storybook art style. Everything about the art is gorgeous and the 3D models contrast really well with the 2D, clearly showing the difference between the inhabitants Lemuria and the real world.The story of the game itself is incredibly short and ends rather abruptly, which makes the ending seem disjointed, rushed, and almost as if the game itself was not finished. A girl, named Aurora, is the daughter of a Duke who loves her very much and her mother has passed away before the start of the story. Eventually the Duke remarries and one night when Aurora goes to bed she falls ill then dies in her sleep, yet awake in a strange land called Lemuria rather than being truly dead. The plot is rather simplistic though the narrator does a great job of conveying it to the player through poetry, much like most of the game's dialogue.The combat system is your typically turn based rpg with the added twist that if you or the enemy take a hit while in the red ""casting"" portion of the action bar, you effecively lose your turn and are send back to the beginning (or 30% for the enemy) of the action bar. Battle effects are cute but not in large variety and later I found that some battles required either a little bit of grinding or some item tossing every few turns. Characters themselves have mostly defined roles in combat (buffer, healer, critical hitter, magic user, etc) minus the main character Aurora who is able to deal decent physical and magical damage (healing as well if you got her DLC).Child of Light also has a very good musical score with almost every piece of music being good to great in quality and fitting the atmosphere of the scene it is used in. However, there are not too many different tunes in the game and you will quickly realise that the game reuses the same tunes constantly. For me this was not a huge issue as I enjoyed the music a lot but later on I did eventually start to tune the music out unconciously.Gameplay is alright as well though nothing too new for anyone who has played a platformer. As Aurora you travel the land of Lemuria on your quest to get back home, finding various chests with loot, fighting enemies, and picking up some sidequests as well. The controls were responsive for me and I do recommend using a controller when you play as I found the keyboard a bit awkward to use for this kind of game. You also get to control a little blue ""firefly"" that can be used to open far away chests, activate switches, slow enemies, heal your party, and provide light in dark rooms. A second person can use the mouse to control the firefly as well, adding what is kind of two player experience to the game. You are also able to craft and equip Oculi, gem stones which grant various buffs to the player depending on the type and slot it is equip to. If you know what colours make what when mixed, you will handle the crafting system just fine.For me the game was basically glitch free as well minus one glitch that has appeared a total of three times, one for each play through. While not game breaking or altering, the glitch many happens when I fight an enemy midjump, which sometimes seems to cause the game to not render Aurora's hair, effectively making her bald for the duration of the battle. Other than that the game gives me stable frame rate the entire time with no other glitches so you should not have to worry about any of that.Lastly, and most disappointing of all, is the fact that the game requires the use of uPlay. Yes, it requires it. If you do not have uPlay you will have to download it to play this game for what I can only conceive as double DRM. If you launch the game through Steam it will automatically open up the uPlay service and have you register the game if you have not yet. Please note that this registration only apply to one uPlay account and cannot be moved so once it's registered you cannot use it with any other account. Should you delete your account or anything the game is effectively gone. After uPlay launches you will have to hit play, at which point uPlay will then launch Steam and then the game itself. This is by far the biggest draw back to the game as uPlay itself is not all that great and it may be a deal breaker for some people who do not already have uPlay on their computers. This also means that you will want to make sure your specs are above the recommended level as your computer will, as far as I know, run both Steam and uPlay at the same time which can heavily drain resources over time.All in all Child of Light is an incredible game, though very short for the price tag given (at full price.) If you like artsy games, turn based rpgs, witty poetry, and a cute story the game may be for you, but just be warned that uPlay will try to impede your progress the first time you boot it up and then less so every time afterwards."
