,Recommended,256290,11114125,"Posted: 7 July, 2014",all,Cuhbrewin,"Child of Light Review (August 5th, 2014 - build 1.0.31711)Quick-read Section(Contains conciseness)What to expect?RPG elements (skill tree/EXP, elemental weaknesses), turn-based combat, platforming, lots of narrative and rhyming, a really nice aesthetic, and an awesome soundtrack.  ...Oh, and Uplay.  Because Ubisoft.Hypothetical and Arbitrary Numerical Rating:9.5/10Would I recommend this game?Hell yes I would.The Apropos Review(Contains rhyming)Gamer, take a seat and relax.And let me express my thoughtOn a story called Child of Light,A game which I have enjoyed a lot.Aurora, an Austrian princess,Finds herself in a magical kingdom -Surrounded by darkness,And begging for freedom.When, lo and behold,A Firefly comes to her aid -Igniculus is its name -A new friendship, madeThe two set off on a journeyTo collect the stars, moon, and sun.For unless they are found,Lemuria is surely done.Characters from across the landAre, to say the least,A band of rag-tag misfits,Including an armored beast.The gameplay is awesome -Half-platformer, Half-RPG -And if I could assign it a grade,The least it would get it is a B.Luckily, the narrative itselfMakes up the scoreFor unlike Call of Duty,The story does not bore.In a time where gamesAre at an all-time low,*I highly suggest this story,Buy it, give it a go!*Note: I do not think the games are at an all-time low but there are disappointing games out there.The In-Depth Review(Contains more detail)So what is Child of Light? Child of Light is a fantasy platforming role-playing game developed by Ubisoft Montreal using the UbiArt Framework engine (the same one used for the more recent Rayman games).  Despite being developed by a branch of Ubisoft, some people consider this game ""Indie"" (especially due to its short playthrough times - 8-10 hours for one playthrough).Story (9/10)The story revolves around a young child named Aurora, born to the Austrian dukeand the Queen of Light, which therefore makes her the ""Child of Light""sometime before the game.  The gameplay opens in 1895 Austria, where Aurora falls into a deep sleep (I believe she is actually considered comatose in Austria), after which she is transported to the magical world of Lemuria, wanting to return back to her home.  She is tasked with finding the stars, the moon, and the sun, in order to return home.  Through the guidance of Igniculus (who is the Firefly that a second player can control), as well as the encounters with the inhabitants of Lemuria - the Populi (Mice), Capilli (Dwarves), and Cynbel (Aquatic folk) - Aurora goes through her own coming-of-age storyand eventually becomes the new Queen of Light, to succeed after her mother in Lemuria.  And that ends the story section because putting any more content will involve serious spoilers.  Surprisingly enough, this is probably the only RPG (or one of few) where I've actually bothered to pay attention to the dialogue to understand the story.As mentioned before, there is a rhyming motif that follows this game because of the way it's presented: like a fairy tale.  The rhyming does seem forced at times but I would assume that's just to keep the story going smoothly.  Luckily you'll only need to deal with rhyming during character dialogue (all of it, including NPCs)...and the objective hint...and the inventory...Gameplay (9/10)Aside from the story and the way it's presented, whatactuallyredeems this game and makes it worth $15?  Well, the turn-based combat is a nice throwback to older JRPGs (while I said Chrono Trigger and FF series, the system more accurately follows the Grandia series).  CoL uses a timeline to gauge who acts when.  There is a long ""Wait"" period followed by a shorter ""Casting"" period.  Hitting an enemy while it's in the ""Casting"" section causes that enemy to be interrupted.  Likewise, if your party members get hit while ""Casting"" they will be interrupted as well.  The battle flow is kind of interrupted if you're waiting for Igniculus to heal your party members or you're struggling about what to do, but other than that the combat mechanics work smoothly.There's also a basic elemental motif, where Fire > Earth  > Lightning (Air) > Water > Fire. (no party members learn Earth magic, but there are Earth-type monsters)  The element of Light, however, is - as TVTropes calls it - an Infinity+1 Element, which means it's basically the OP element of the game.  Aurora is,surprise, surprise, considering she's the ""Child of Light"",theonlycharacter in thegamewho can use Light magic, which is super effective against Dark-type monsters and not resisted byanyelement. (Even though Aurora herself iskindavery squishy in the beginning)The platforming itself is easy enough to manuever, although the graphics do obscure which parts of the world are able to be traversed and which parts aren't.  Considering I'm not much of a fan for platformers, I found the platforming quite do-able.  Plus, the platforming leaves room for exploration.Some elements of the game are basic versions of more modern RPGs, such as the equipment section (which actually isn't ""equipment"", just gems you can craft and socket into weapon, defensive, and support slots) and the skill trees (which reminded me of FF10's Sphere Grid or FF13's Crystarium, and is also highly reminiscent of Far Cry 3's skill trees).CoL offers a good 8-10 hour playthrough, depending on how long it takes you to progress through the platforming and bosses.  (It took me 10 on casual... but I hear you can do it in 8 or less)  There is also NG+ (New Game+), where you can restart the story with higher-leveled enemies but keep all your oculi (gems), skills, and inventory items.As a person who normally likes shooting up people in FPS games, this is a nice game to enjoy on the side while taking a break from all the bullets.Music (10/10), Aesthetics, Graphics (10/10)*this is not my area of expertiseThe music is well-composed (by Béatrice Martin, aka Cœur de pirate).  It touched my heart during cutscenes/dialogue and invigorated me during battles and bosses.  The game engine (UbiArt Framework) makes for some really nice 2/2.5D aesthetics.  There's also some 3D graphics for the battle animations.  To me, the aesthetics are pretty amazing and I enjoy them (a lot).  Er...other than that though, I really don't pay attention to graphics that much... :PThe VerdictFinal Score: 38/40 = 9.5/10Is this game good? Yes.  It keeps the RPG genre simple and instead focuses on a deep and very enjoyable narrative as well as outstanding graphics.Would I recommend this? Wholly and highly.  If you don't mind the Uplay that is.Is it worth the money? Yep.Get this game! ...Do it."
