76561198025434087,Recommended,256290,22125595,"Posted: 29 March, 2016",all,robertdrake910,"Overall this is an excellent game.  Shockingly it  brings both excitement and tension to ATB style turn based combat, a feat few games can manage.Starting with the bad to get it out of the way:-The characters and story seemed to have been designed with the hopes of being whimsical and wonderful, but to me they fell flat.  It doesn't help that all speech is in rhyme (with the exception of one character), a feature I found more annoying than endearing.-The ending is very abrupt, and leaves one with the sense that the developers were encouraged to cut the game short in favor of other projects.  My play through was less than 15 hours, even with a hearty helping of side-quests and general exploration.Now on to the good:-Tricks, traps, and puzzles are scattered throughout the levels as well as a plethora of useful treasures. This makes exploration both interesting and satisfying.-The mouse is fully integrated into the game in the form of a helpful light spirit who can gather certain treasures and stun enemies.  I was surprised just how engrossing this small addition can be, as it draws even more of your attention into the game as you consider both what to do with your character and her spirit companion simultaneously.-All party members have unique specialties and are readily swappable during combat, opening a wide strategic field from which to choose your methods for defeating the enemy.  Played on Expert mode, you will need them all!-Played on Expert mode, combat is tense and thrilling.  Each character, both ally and enemy, appears on the shared ATB bar, moving at different speeds according to their speed.  When they select an action on their turn, they then move into the ""Casting"" section of the bar.  If struck during the casting phase, they will be interrupted and set back significantly on the bar!  Being that your spirit companion can be used to slow monsters (yay for mouse integration!), you must now carefully consider how to manipulate the bar to ensure that the enemies are the ones to be stunned rather than your party, and mistakes can turn even a normal battle into a desperate struggle!  This extra dimension is, quite frankly, genius.  I have never been so engaged in ATB style combat.Overall, though Child of Light is a short game, I would still absolutely recommend it for the current $15 price tag.  Don't miss out on this one!"
