,Recommended,256290,16038998,"Posted: 28 May, 2015",all,Lusoka,"First and foremost, there is no reason to tell you it is pretty or ugly, or it sounds wonderful or you should invest in ear plugs.It is completely an opinion thing that has no real relevance in a review. Unless it is causing an actual issue in the game (Which this game actually does have one.). There isn't a point to say anything about it.This game has a lovely combat system stemming with many tactical options if you figure and decide to use them. The little wisp you get is not only for puzzle solving and healing from smacking traps and the like, but for combat as well. All this is implemented wonderfully, though I will say, it is alot easier to manage with a mouse then a controller, since it slowly moves towards the location with weight.The platforming this game has, while mild, does what is needed and doesn't unfairly damage the player in any real cheap ways, except for maybe one area, but there are usually plenty of healing around, even on the hardest of settings.The story seemed well thought out, at least to me, supposedly there was more to the ending from what I hear, but it ended ok. One thing about it peevs me a little bit, but I'll mention that later.Now the irksome stuff. Let's start with characters. Despite the characters having multiple paths, there are only so many that really matter. The game only really has two mages in the game, and once you figure that out, it feels more like a punishment when you go down a less optimal path. Alot of the characters go into this category. I don't mind mentioning this one character, he is remotely close to the start. You'll run across a wizard who can do fire/water/lighting. Now, you can split them up and maybe get all the medium single target spells, OR you can go all Lighting, get a dmg bonus to all spells by 30% at the end of the chain and as a added bonus, most things tend to be weak to lighting late game....ya, not really much variety when you screw over the fire and water builders who play the game.This kinda goes with most characters, since if you decide to do that sorta thing, then you need an attacker, removing thefirst character from the other tree, yadda. There also is something nasty about the main character if you decide to go melee instead of magic and vice versa. For me, she skyrocketed Int, the other way was str, It seems to balance out more if ya go into both early, but I saw most intellect growth for about 90% of levels.This is an art issue, it doesn't happen often. The background will get in the way at certain points and it can be very easy to run into damaging objects. Bout it there. Ran across a glitch where my main character didn't have her flowing locks. Was kinda funny. Think is was a resolution issue, also caused slowdown.My first run was a 3 speed, 2nd was a 5 speed. Healing is so much better on 5 speed. Like 3 speed is basically the equivalent to 1 with how slow the healing can be, 5 is just snap done. It just feels really slow. Probably gonna make me a 5er for life.Overall it's a good game, the variety feels like it could use more to make different replays worthwhile. You totally could do melees and such, but it's just extending battles way to long for no real reason or benefit. It's the only real gripe I have with the game. The difficulty is about medium I think once you figure out how things work, which the game either straight up tells you how to do it, or just the littlest of experimentation can lead you to.(Example: I figured out I could heal while the game was paused for my action.)Little tidbit. While I don't like having another thing open for what seems no real reason, it is actually way better then if steam launched it. One main reason. The achievements can actually lead to you getting something. Like, omg right, your unlocks in game are actually useful? :O Amazing. Now I don't know if it is trying to shovel trojans and♥♥♥♥♥♥at me or slowing my computer down, but I could really get behind the trend of ""Achievements do something.""Now to end on something witty and clever. *Burp*"
