76561198066006167,Recommended,256290,13442272,"Posted: 18 December, 2014",all,Josh,"Preliminary note:  Child of Light requires UPlay to... well, play.  I personally haven't had issues with this, but if you don't like the idea of handing over your personal data to yet another steam knock-off, well, you've been warned then.Aside from that, Child of Light is a really well-done game, easily one of my personal contenders for Game of the Year.  I've played through it twice, completing both the normal game and the game+ variant.  I'm even considering playing it through a third time because I continue to find new details each time I play through it.  Not to mention, the music is just wonderful.  If anything, this masterpiece is worth it just for the soundtrack alone.To understand why this game is good, understand that every detail in this game feels like it was put there with a purpose.  Everything from the background music, to the shades in the landscape, to the characters you meet, to the art of the landscapes themselves, all feel well-placed with regards to the story.  Everything follows the story arch beautifully.  There's very little backtracking involved (unless you want to look for extra treasures), so it feels as though the story progresses at a nice pace.  It may sound like the game is narrow, but it doesn't feel that way at all as there are a lot of optional areas you can explore.Even the combat, which one would suspect could most easily fall victim to redundancy, is very well done.  Almost every chapter, you are introduced to new combat styles and enemies, so it never really gets old.My only criticism of the game is that the end of the last chapter feels a tad rushed, and apparently it is because there was a section between the end of the previous chapter and the final boss that was omitted, per the creative director in a reddit Q&A.  And it is a real shame too, because I just want more!If you like fairy tales, JRPGs, normal RPGs, story-driven games, or even just Coeur du Pirate, you should play this game.  Nowadays, I rarely spend more than $15 on any base game given the frequency of steam sales, but this game was worth every cent and then some."
