,Recommended,256290,21908724,"Posted: 18 March, 2016",all,Nite_Traveler,"A masterful work of art from start to finish, and a delight to play.Here we have the story of Aurora, a young girl from Austria who is suddenly transported to an ancient and mysterious land, suddenly having to fend for herself against the strange creatures and dark forces that inhabit it. Along the course of her journey, she'll meet different types of creatures, some human or human-like, and others of a more animal nature, (often I was reminded of Zelda games) and several will join her team. As expected for an RPG, they each have different strengths and weaknesses, and you can hone their skills to build your dream team. And together, the team will travel the land, fight monsters, solve a few puzzles, and try to help Aurora get back home to her father.I'm not huge into RPGs, so it takes a really good one to capture my attention for very long. This game as an RPG is not only incredibly fun to play, but it's also very innovative in a lot of ways. Turn-based combat gets a bit of a twist here, with a sort of timeline that determines when you and your enemies will strike. The speed varies based on your stats, what attack you're using, how fast your enemies are, and if any status effects are applied. If an enemy strikes you while you're preparing to attack, your attack may be interupted. But if you're clever, you can also use this against an enemy and interupt their attack. I don't know if this approach is completely original, but it's the first I've seen of it, and to me it made turn-based combat a whole lot more interesting. Every move you make can be timed and strategized to defeat opponents with different types or strengths. There's also a Pokemon-like element system where elemental attacks can be used against enemies that are weak to that type. And you can instantly swap out a member of your party for another one if you need to change up your strategy.Another nice addition is that you have a blue fairy, Igniculus, who you can contol independently of Aurora. He can help you solve puzzles, gather items out of Aurora's reach, do basic healing and even slow down enemies during combat. His energy is a renewable resource that's an essential part of the gameplay. You'll get used to controlling two characters onscreen at the same time, and using both of them to complete tasks or strategize for combat. Igniculus can even be controlled by a second player if you have another controller.I can't say enough nice things about the look of the game. Everything is rendered in a beautiful watercolor style, and some areas are simply incredible to explore. The screenshots just don't do it justice - you have to see for yourself how good this game looks. The soundtrack is also beautiful and very appropriate, and the combat music was done well as to not be annoyingly repetitive considering how much you'll hear it.The leveling system is very generous, some might say too generous, but it helps the game to not feel like too much of a grind. I enjoyed the combat so much that I battled with every enemy I encountered - it just never got boring to me. Leveling up gives you skill points which you can use to improve your stats, attacks, defense, and other abilities. There are also items in the world that can permanently increase your stats, as well as Oculi which are crystals that can be crafted. I ignored this for a while, but once I understood how it worked, I became obsessed with Oculi. They are fun to craft and help you plan the strategy of your team by adding bonus effects to their attacks and defense.The world is pretty big, but you have fast travel which unlocks automatically as you discover new areas. There are a handful of side quests that you can take on if you'd like. Some of them get a bit backtracky but I didn't mind it - generally the longer the quest, the better the reward. For the main quest, exploration is very important. It may take you a while to figure out where you need to go next as there's very little handholding here. You just get a slight hint about what you're supposed to be doing, and that's it. I found this very refreshing.The story is pretty simple, but it holds together well and I found myself invested in the world-building as I went along. I loved the dialogue - most characters speak in rhymes and riddles - and this helped to build the characters a bit and show how they relate to one another. I particularly enjoyed when Igniculus asked Aurora questions about her world or what it's like to be human. Her answers were often simple, yet profound and moving coming from a young girl.Overall a very enjoyable game. If you liked Ori and the Blind Forest, Dust: An Elysian Tail, or other games like those, you may enjoy this one even more. I still have yet to finish Ori because the difficulty started to ruin my enjoyment of the game. If something simpler and lighter than that is your wish, Child of Light will grant it. Took me about 15 hours to finish, but I took my time exploring and engaging in every battle and side quest. You could likely finish the main story in half that time if you wanted to.10/10 for me, very well done."
76561198064101186,Recommended,256290,30733145,Posted: 25 March,all,SeaSlug,"A beautiful game, art, soundtrack, and story alike."
,Not Recommended,256290,21894363,"Posted: 17 March, 2016",all,lilygoatgruff,"Very pretty game but gets old quick. Graphics laggy, slow plot, takes too long to get through dialogue, bosses aren't interesting."
,Recommended,256290,30727030,Posted: 25 March,all,Hostile,Truly Beautiful. The soundtrack and story alone make this game worth picking up. It's fantastic.
76561198057548220,Recommended,256290,12319203,"Posted: 1 October, 2014",all,Zatanna,"Beautiful is the only word that comes to mind when asked to describe Child of Light. From the amazing fantasy world of Lemuria to the delicate flow of the soundtrack and from the immersive combat system to the underlying theme of the story, Child of Light becomes the beacon of both hope and inspiration that a great RPG can exist in this generation of gaming.The world of Child of Light is incredibly stunning and very well realised as the fairy tale setting comes to life as though right out of a children's bedtime book. Reality is but an ember within this brightly shining flame of fantasy galore and I can't help but stop and marvel at the beautiful world during my travels through Lemuria.This existing beauty is largely due to the fact that everything within the game is made to look as though it was painted in watercolour. Whether you're floating around as Aurora or admiring the character portraits during conversations, the art style brings out a sense of nostalgia and fondness, reigniting the subconscious memory of famous old fairy tales. Do they have talking mice? Check. How about midget magicians? Check. Sword in the stone? Double check. All of these, in aesthetically attractive watercolour art.The world is fully fleshed out with a soundtrack that is truly remarkable, memorable and addictive. As you cruise through the skies of Lemuria, you can't help but give your mind over to the soothing draw of the violin or sway your head to the catchy tune of the piano. The solo effort of Béatrice Martin creates a bridge to your emotions that latches on and never lets go, long after finishing the game. The battle music, however, makes use of a whole orchestra to generate fiery fierceness and a potent cheer during its climax that would be sure to instill an everlasting feeling of power and hope within the player.Gameplay in Child of Light is akin to what I would call a turn-based active time interactive system. Why interactive? This feature comes from your buddy, Igniculus, who can be used to slow enemies and heal Aurora and her allies. The active time turn-based system acts independently of Igniculus (controlled with the mouse) and depending on your timing in slowing your enemies, can be very useful or horribly detrimental. This dynamic shows off even during the first battle and is something I found to be engaging and very fun to play with.Finally, Child of Light tells the story of Aurora, a young princess who finds herself in Lemuria, in search of her father who is at death's bed. While the story remains as such, the underlying theme is what I found to be the actual journey, the actual idea of the game. Child of Light isn't just a simple fairy tale, it's a light-hearted coming-of-age story. Even after finishing the game, it's strange to say I've become attached to Aurora's journey and maturity.The only gripe I have with the game is the length of it because having done all the side-quests, optional bosses and collected all the confessions, I've only logged in about 13 hours. Of course, the price compensates for that and I'm quite used to playing properly lengthy JRPGs which obviously does not compare.Child of Light, to me, was well worth the money and I can not be happier to say that such a great RPG is now present on the PC. The game was short but incredibly sweet and I can't help but keep diving back into it, not to do anything else but gaze at and absorb its beauty. After all, having the ability to fly, I wanted to simply float along and smile."
