,Recommended,256290,22788475,"Posted: 3 May, 2016",all,Sweetz,"It took me quite a while to get around to playing Child of Light, but I'm glad I did.  It's a beautiful game and it was nice to play something with a JRPG-like gameplay format, but with a more reasonable length.That said, I have to air some gripes with the battle system since it makes up the bulk of the game's gameplay.  There's no one thing massively wrong with it, but there are several little problems that add up.Primarily, you can only have 2 characters in battle at a time, but the characters still fall into typical RPG archetypes of fighter, caster, support.  Only having 2 character types on hand at a given time versus the more typical 3 is annoying.  The game does allow you to swap out party members on the fly, but frequently needing to swap in a character just to cast a few buffs and then swap back to your damage dealer became annoying.What makes the swapping even worse in a way, is that the game places such an emphasis on elemental weakness that for 90% of the time I stuck with the same two characters who together could cast all spells needed to hit the weakness of most enemies - always swapping back to them after another character taking a single action to heal or buff.  Half the party members are support characters that aren't useful except to perform one action and then be immediately swapped out. Using the same two characters for the most of the game leads to a real lack of variety in the battles, even over the game's short length.Lastly, the game has a mechanism by which you can interrupt enemy attacks and set them back on the turn timeline, but late game enemies and bosses punish you for performing an interrupt with sometimes very severe counterattacks, rendering something that is a key mechanic and encouraged in normal battles into something that needs to be avoided.  I mean, if you want to have one ""gimmick"" boss battle that subverts the game mechanics ok, fine, but doing this with almost every boss fight is no good.As said, I still enjoyed the game in spite of my gripes with the battle system.  It's still better than many actual JRPGs where 99% of the battles are mindnumbingly boring, but I felt with a few tweaks it could have been a much better game."
