76561198167970698,Recommended,256290,28984376,Posted: 3 January,all,ryan431bball,"I enjoyed this game but was not completely blown away by the story.  I've played through twice and managed to finish the game in one day on my second run.  The battle mechanics are the best part of this game.  I actually found it easier to  play with a mouse rather than a controller.  The art and music were amazing, well worth its price; if it is on sale, it becomes a must buy.7/10 Story9/10 Music/Atmosphere10/10 Artwork9/10 Battle System8.5/10 Overall"
76561198052436469,Recommended,256290,28952059,Posted: 2 January,all,Hekateras,"Beautiful game in terms of style but don't expect too much from it in terms of writing. Pleasant, relaxing experience for when you need to retreat into an uncomplicated fairytale world, but this is not the game to blow you away and capture your imagination for years to come.Pros:- The art style and music make for a great aesthetic, you feel like you're caught in a living watercolour painting.- Combat can be quite fun. There is no real 'one size fits all' combat strategy as different monsters require different strategies to defeat, and figuring out the best strategy for a new monster or boss fight can be quite fun. Its up to you if you seek out every encounter to gain XP or avoid all encounters but the necessary.- The level design is quite nice and there's something very pleasing and relaxing about exploring it, especially with Aurora's flight ability.- The worldbuilding is quite fascinating.Cons:- Levelling is too quick and easy. In terms of difficulty, I found 'normal' mode too easy once you got the hang of the game. Thankfully you can change modes mid-game.- All dialogue and narration is in rhyme. While the developers likely felt this created a certain feel, too often the rhymes are forced and cringeworthy and it comes at the expense of the dialogue.- The story is very... formulaic, in depth, and plays the 'good vs. evil' tropes very straight. There are some attempts at layers with the implication that The Whole Thing Might Have Been A Dying Dream (can it be a coincidence that the first companion you meet is named Rubella? Which is also the name of a disease.. maybe I'm searching too hard for something that isn't there) and all in her head, but they're not explored and won't give you any satisfaction. The protagonist changes from a little girl to a teen seemingly spontaneously mid-story and that's not really explained either beyond the vague understanding that it's meant to be symbolic of her personal growth or something.- On a similar level, though the game tries to create a sense of strong camaraderie and Friendship(TM) between the ragtag group of heroes and treats it as a given in-story, the short snippets of intra-pary dialogue feels like little more than lip service to it. Not helped by the fact that you as the protag can never actually choose what you say, so there's a sense of bystander rather than participant in all interactions with the NPCs. As such, I feel like you never really get fully invested in identifying with the protagonist.On the whole I'd say this is a game of style over substance. Good enough for the price I bought it at, but I consistently felt like I was expecting to like it more than I did. It's like all the elements were there separately that woke up my nostalgia and conditioned me to like this game through reminders of older and possibly better-written games, but none of it came together into anything meaningful. So it was okay, but it could have been great."
