,Recommended,256290,30079528,Posted: 21 February,all,TwiliSailor,"Child of Light is a beautifully simple introductory RPG from Ubisoft. The story plays out like a fairytale which at first glance may seem campy, but once you delve deeper its a wonderful coming of age tale. There are plot twists and events that you wouldn't expect from such a child-like game which rather than seeming distasteful add a lot to character motivation. Gameplay uses a more simplified version of the ATB system seen in Final Fantasy games. The core mechanics revolve around a turn based system where you all use the same timeline and can push back or cancel each others attacks to gain advantage.It's not a hard game by any means but has a suprising amount of depth as you advance through the chapters. It's also not very long, a first playthrough might average about 10-12 hours depending on the difficulty you choose. The dialogue can get a bit panderous as all text is spoken in rhyme. There are some lines where you can tell they ran out of ideas and couldn't get something to fit. But in all the only dissapointment is that the ending seems rushed. Plot points are hastily explained before the games final battle and with more time it could have been an amazing way to finish the story.Child of Light is stunning. The way it uses music, atmosphere, graphics, story and gameplay altogether show that not all games from large developers have to be Triple-A to be good. One of the only games worth installing Uplay for."
,Recommended,256290,31053349,Posted: 9 April,all,Jon Snow,"This game is a unquie blend of many mechanics that worked really well and some that failed miserably.Lets talk about the art and music score first because by far that is the strongest asset to this game. The music is phenonmenal and really set the mood. The water color art style was truly a pleasure to my eyes and exciting to see each new part of every world/level.The story, simple and sweet. The rhyming never got tiring for me and each character had their own personal touch to the world which was nice and some were very creative like the mice who live on the back of a giant and travel abroad as traders of all products. The world was more fasinating than anything and was fun to just explore and get lost.The fighting/oculi system. Ok so here's the negative, it's not huge since you can bypass most fights (think chrono trigger style battle initation) but with all the detail spent creating this world they didn't spend much time with the battle mechanics, that other reviewers have already mentioned. I don't know, I really didn't enjoy it at all it felt really superficial compared to how much effort went into everything else.I recommend this product because I think games like this should be supported in the sense that I enjoy this type of ""out of box"" thinking, we can only hope that if they're gonna make an RPG that they take some classic mechanics from well worked systems."
