,Recommended,256290,20596780,"Posted: 17 January, 2016",all,Deadaghram,"Claiming Uplay ruins this game is like saying your significant other farted and that’s why you got a divorce (unless your issue is Uplay won't let you even start the game because if your spuse is dead, go get remarried, at your own pace of course).Child of Light is comparable to classic RPG from the Playstation/2 era.  It's a bit different in that the main character isn't a brooding or hyperactive teen who grows into a god but a child just looking for her father’s love who may actually be the weakest character in the game - although, depending on playstyles and upgrade paths, this can be argued.  The Lady Aurora is a child of unknown age, but clearly very young, who falls into a coma-like/dies status at the start of the game.  While in that coma dream/afterlife she travels to the World of Lemuria where she does typical video game stuff: meet people, gain battle ready comrades, have some allies become enemies and enemies become allies, defeat monsters, do stuff with the sun and the mood, grow both emotional and physically, save a world or two.  Ya know, same old, same old.  While she's in Lemuria, though, her father, The Duke falls into severe depression leaving him unable to anything about the impending destruction by flood of his (land-locked) Austria.  Side note, Duke is a made-up title as Austria stopped calling its rulers Dukes in either 1365 or 1804 if you consider Archduke to be different from a normal Duke.  The more you know!The combat of Child of Light is classic turn-based with a timeline allowing for speed to be an important factor in how fast you go and cast spells/skills.  With speed, and a quick attack cast, you have the ability to interrupt an opponent (or get interrupted) out of an attack and spend them back to the beginning-ish of the timeline.  Each character has their own strengths and weakness and their own purpose in combat.  Wither that be to cast a certain elemental type or just to soak of damage.  Characters can be switched on the fly with only the cost of timeline resetting.The timeline is also how the game becomes ""multi-player"".  The second player controls a ball of light (Firefly) named Ignatius who has the ability to slow enemies.  He can also heal allies and restore MP using flower pollen (which may have an official name I don't recall).  Out of combat, Ignatius can light up the dark and that's all he can do.  Good luck having fun, Player 2.  If it's just single player you control both characters.New Skills are learned at level up and are used to customize each character.  Do you want a character to be physical or magical?  Learn a stronger single target spell or one that hits everyone?  Learn a Buff or a debuff?  Etc.Combat may be turn-based but exploration is platform-esq.  Unlike all other platform games, CoL has a flight mechanic that is active full time, whenever you call on it.  There are no limits on when or where (besides things being in your way) so it allows for hidden and hard to reach passageways and secrets.  Most of the things you're looking for are other characters (I almost missed Rubella - the first combat eligible ally) and confessions - which are diary and poems that either give backstory on the land of Lemuria or connect Lemuria to the real world somehow.  There's just as much upward to see than is side-to-side.The art style is stunning.  Not just the visually but audibly as well.  Visually, Child of Light is something out of a prodigy’s watercolor dream.  I say prodigy because watercoloring is something most people consider childish which works because of Aurora’s age.  There's a lot of duality, of sorts, in Child of Light, not sure how much is intentionally but it's there.  When it comes to dialogue, it's a poet’s heaven.  Everyone speaks in A-B-C-B rhyme (meaning the second and fourth sentences rhyme).  It can be a bit painful at times as characters struggle to fit the scheme but this is, somewhat rare, and overall, I thought it was marvelous.  I'd love to see more games do about different styles of speaking rather than boring spoken prose.The Music in Child of Light is nothing sort of a masterpiece.  Even if you don't like the game then at least give the music a listen once or twice.  It's largely (this very amateur music thinks is a) piano quartet with a few string instruments and a piano but there are also a few full orchestral tracks as well.  There's the occasional woodwind for good measure here and there as well.  Cœur de Pirate came out of nowhere (to me, at least) and she quickly became one of my favorite artists.  When it comes down to it, though, music is hard to describe through words, especially for those who aren't masters of the craft.  It's also very subjective so here's some official sources:iTunesSpotifySadly, though, the official OST doesn't contain all of the tracks.  As a matter of fact, some of the best stuff is only in the game itself.  Since no one is losing money off me posting it, here's the rest of the tracks:Gamerip on YoutubeThe only downside to Child of Light is it lacks much replay value for most players.  You can always change your battle tactics and focus on something else but the story is linear, with only one ending.  That's not a dealbreaker to a lot of people, especially if you're a part of the ""classic"" era of gaming, but if it is, then wait for it to go on sale to try to maximize gameplay/cost efficiency.If you're an artist of any style, you're going find plenty to love in Child of Light.  If you're a gamer of any style (outisde of those who only FPS multiplayers, perhaps), you're going to find plenty to love.  This is a game all about light vs dark (Aurora being light, both in the game and IRL, and story related dark references characters, good v evil, the epic of the game it's self v perceived Uplay).  Blaming Uplay for why you won't buy the game or bother giving it an actual review/play though is a poor excuse (unless you legitimately can't get it to work).  You have to log into your Microsoft account to use your PC, your Steam account for games, your bank account for banking, etc.  You’re the only one missing out by not playing this."
